Timber shop signs surrounded by decorative stucco mouldings. Sandstone and limestone ashlar to archways of ground floor. Stucco scroll detailing flanking first floor windows. Engaged Ionic columns to ground floor windows. Timber top hung outward opening windows with moulded render window surrounds. Timber fixed windows with timber glazed panelled doors to ground floor, and timber glazed panelled double leaf door with carved limestone lintel flanked by engaged Ionic columns with fanlight above surrounded by limestone archivolt. Wrought-iron double leaf gate to laneway arch. Timber sliding sash arched stairway window visible to rear.

NAME: The Rock Inn
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built 1893, with decorative stucco façade. Now in use as public house. Pitched caulked natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with nap render quoins, decorative window mouldings and projecting metal brackets with shop signs. Top hung outward opening uPVC windows with painted stone sills and moulded decorative window surrounds. Timber fixed window to ground floor with timber panelled doors having toplights, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: O' Flynn Interiors Ltd.
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay three-storey former house, built 1924, with recessed porch to entrance to ground floor and having single- and three-storey extensions to rear. Now in use as retail outlet. Pitched caulked purple slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Corrugated-sheet and hipped purple slate roof to extension. Painted nap rendered walls with render decorative mouldings and render quoins. Timber painted shopfront and timber panelling to ground floor. Timber sliding sash and uPVC top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills and moulded render window surrounds. Fixed aluminium window to ground floor with timber matchboard door having toplight and timber glazed doors to recessed porch.

NAME: Batt Coffey
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey with dormer accommodation former house, built c. 1820, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched natural slate roof with mineralised felt repairs and having mineralised felt flat roofs to dormers. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with natural slate roof cladding to dormer windows and having exposed rubble stone visible to rear. Timber sliding sash windows to dormers. Timber top hung outward opening and timber side hung outward opening windows with painted stone sills to second floor. Timber fixed windows with timber glazed double leaf doors to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: Infinity
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace two-bay three-storey with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1820, now in use as offices and retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with hipped natural slate roof, rooflights and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with painted brick below shop window. Timber top hung outward opening windows with painted concrete sills to upper floors. Fixed timber window with canted timber shop sign above to ground floor. Timber glazed door to ground floor.

NAME: Jackie Power
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1810, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rooflight and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with canted timber sign to first floor. Rubble limestone visible to rear. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window with timber glazed double leaf doors having toplights above, surrounded by pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor.
Limestone archway, built c. 1860, as entrance to market, now with nap rendered wall above. Tooled limestone ashlar to piers and arch with render above.

NAME: Caball
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former pair of houses, built c. 1830, sited at angle to street. Now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete barging to party wall, cast-iron rooflight, cast-iron rainwater goods, and having nap rendered chimneystack. Painted nap rendered walls with painted brick to ground floor. Roughcast rendered to side walls. Rubble stone with brick infill flue to party wall to north-east. Timber paired windows with dividing mullions and painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber sliding sash tripartite window to first floor. Timber fixed windows to ground floor.

NAME: Kerry Bookshop
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1810, with curved projection to rear. Now in use as retail outlet. Metallised felt flat roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with painted brick to ground floor. Timber sliding sash tripartite windows with painted stone sills. Timber fixed window and timber glazed door with toplight to ground floor, having painted timber shop sign above. Timber top hung outward opening window to side wall.

NAME: Caball
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1830, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled painted nap rendered walls with canted timber shop sign over ground floor. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullion and painted stone sill to third floor. Fixed timber windows to first and second floor. Recessed timber glazed door to ground floor with tiled porch area.

NAME: G. Connolly Jewellers
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1890, with three-storey extension to rear.  Now in use as retail outlet. Pitched purple slate roof with projecting parapet and having flat roof to extension to rear. Painted nap rendered walls with giant order decorative pilasters to upper three floors to right hand side corner. Corrugated-iron cladding to extension. Timber sliding sash windows in segmental-arched openings with moulded reveals and hood mouldings, render plat bands at sill levels to upper floors. Timber fixed window and timber glazed door to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Tiled entrance porch area.

NAME: First Active
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1855, now in use as bank. Pitched artificial slate roof with galvanised rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls with marble cladding to ground floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Fixed timber windows and half glazed timber double leaf doors to ground floor with timber painted shop sign above. Tiles to entrance steps.

NAME: New Gent
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1855, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with galvanised gutter. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors.  Timber fixed window and timber glazed door with toplight to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: Cleary's Photography
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace single-bay three-storey former house, built 1853, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and galvanised gutter. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls with canted projection to side wall. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Glazed curtain walling to ground floor and timber glazed door with painted timber shop sign above.

NAME: Kelliher's Hardware
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey former gasworks, built c. 1900, now in use as store for hardware shop. Flat roof of concrete slab on steel beams with replacement plywood sheeting on timber rafters to upper level roof. Red brick walls. Fixed steel windows in arched openings, with louvered metal and corrugated metal sheet to clerestory. Red brick and concrete block boundary wall. Detached two-bay two-storey boiler house to west with flat roof arched openings and brick walls.

NAME: Carraig Down
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace three-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1850, now in use as shop. Pitched and hipped roof with uPVC rainwater goods. Rubble stone and brick panel walls to ground floor with timber shopfront. Cement rendered walls to upper floors having projecting metal bracket with painted sign. Single and paired timber sliding sash windows with painted stone or concrete sills to upper floors. Stucco label moulding to second floor west window to Bridge Street. Timber fixed window to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: Celtic Cabs
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1830, now also in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights, rendered chimneystack and uPVC rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins to upper floors. Channelled rendered walls to ground floor with projecting moulded cornice above and having painted timber sign. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with stone sills and moulded surrounds to upper floors. Fixed uPVC to ground floor and aluminium glazed doors with top hung outward opening toplight. Limestone threshold to door to right hand side and concrete step up front door of retail outlet. Timber sliding sash windows with brick flat arches over to rear elevation. Rubble stone outbuilding and boundary walls to rear, having recess to north wall with segmental brick arch.

Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1940, with projecting glazed porch to ground floor central bay. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods and having flat roof to porch. Painted nap rendered walls with render quoins and plat bands. Timber sliding sash windows to first floor, mullioned to ground floor, all with painted stone sills. Timber top-hung outward opening and side-hung outward opening windows with painted concrete sills and timber half glazed door to porch. Nap rendered boundary walls with concrete copings and cast-iron double leaf gates.

Detached two-bay single-storey gate lodge, built 1907. Hipped artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Roughcast rendered walls with render plinth. Render decorative band over bay window and render panels below windows. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills and render surrounds. Timber panelled door with render surround.

NAME: Park na Doon
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey house, built 1882, three central bays are gabled to front and rear facades.  Two-bay single-storey extensions to left hand side/south-east. Pitched natural slate roof with crested ridge tiles, nap rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Red brick walls to ground floor, nap rendered walls with render decorative plat bands to first floor and having red brick moulded string course between ground floor and first floor. Red brick to extensions. Timber sliding sash and timber side-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Bay windows to rear and north-west facades. Recessed timber panelled door with decorative render surround having polychrome tiles to floor and walls of porch. Nap rendered walls to entrance with piers, wrought-iron gates and railings. Tennis court to site.

Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1885, with extension to left hand side and three-bay two-storey extension to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Single-pitched roof to left hand side extension and pitched roof to rear extension. Painted nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Roughcast rendered boundary walls to front elevation. Rubble stone boundary walls with timber panelled door having red brick surround, corrugated metal double leaf gates, and with rubble and breeze block infill construction to side wall.

Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1950, gabled right hand side bay and having central projecting glazed porch. Two-bay single-storey extension to left hand side. Hipped artificial slate roof, pitched to gabled bay, with nap rendered chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods, flat roof to garage, and timber bargeboards to gabled bay. Pebble dashed walls with render quoins and plat bands. Timber mullioned sash windows with concrete sills and render surrounds. Timber glazed porch with timber glazed door. Timber matchboard door and garage door to extension. Pebble dashed boundary walls with concrete copings and cast-iron double leaf gates.

NAME: Clonalour House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1915, with bay windows and porch projection to ground floor. Several single- and two-bay extensions. Hipped natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots, cast-iron rainwater goods, hipped single-pitched artificial slate roof to bay windows and flat roof to porch. Pitched natural slate roof and flat roofs to rear extensions. Nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber glazed double leaf doors with render surrounds. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows to extensions.

Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1915, with gabled bay having bay windows to left hand side. Two-storey extension to rear with adjoining single-storey extension. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights, uPVC and cast-iron rainwater goods, single-pitched artificial slate roof porch roof, timber bargeboards to gabled bay and crested ridge tiles. Red brick and cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with moulded stone sills and painted stone lintel. Timber panelled door with side and toplights. Red brick boundary walls.

End-of-terrace three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1915, right hand side bay is gabled. Two-storey extension to rear with adjoining single-storey extension. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights, cement rendered chimneystack, uPVC rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gabled bay and single-pitched artificial slate roof to porch. Red brick and cement rendered walls with string courses at sill levels. uPVC top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills and lintels. Timber half glazed double leaf doors with side and toplights. Cement rendered boundary walls with concrete copings and wrought-iron railings.

NAME: Tralee CIE Credit Union
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey former house with gablet, built 1896, left hand side and right hand side bays are projecting.  Now in use as Credit Union. Pitched artificial slate roof with red brick chimneystacks and uPVC rainwater goods. Snecked ashlar limestone walls with red brick quoins. Aluminium top-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills and curved stone lintels above. Aluminium glazed door. Snecked sandstone boundary walls with limestone tooled ashlar copings and cushion ashlar piers.

Detached six-bay single-storey warehouse, built 1859. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with red brick chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Snecked roughly dressed ashlar sandstone walls with limestone quoins. Boarded openings with red brick surrounds and limestone sills to windows. Corrugated metal sheet door with concrete surround.
Circular-plan iron turntable with railway tracks on timber support, with iron movable mechanism as support, built 1859.

NAME: Casement Station
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey station block with six-bay single-storey flanking wings to right hand side and left hand side, built 1859, glazed entrance porch added to left hand side bays. Hipped artificial slate roof with limestone ashlar chimneystacks, uPVC rainwater goods and crested ridge tiles. Snecked ashlar limestone walls with string course at sill level first floor and moulded string course over first floor openings. Timber sliding sash windows in segmental-arched opening with raised limestone surrounds and sills. Timber panelled double leaf doors with toplights and raised limestone surrounds. uPVC glazed double leaf doors to porch. Concrete block/cement rendered/grey brick boundary walls with cast metal railings and gates. Bus shelter to site.
Single-arch limestone bridge with limestone ashlar voussoirs, built c. 1850. Roughly dressed limestone walls with dressed limestone copings to south wall and limestone upright copings to north wall.

NAME: Caherina House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1910, with three-bay two-storey extension to rear. Hipped caulked natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Pitched caulked natural slate roof to extension. Painted nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floor. Timber glazed door with toplight. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing timber mullions to ground floor. Timber sliding sash and top-hung outward-opening windows to extension. Concrete block boundary walls.

Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1850, with single-bay single-storey extension to left hand side/west. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Timber top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows to extension. Roughcast rendered boundary wall with cast-iron gate.

Detached five-bay two-storey house, built c. 1810, with glass house to left hand side and porch surrounding front door. Extension to right hand side rear. Hipped natural slate roof with concrete bargings, nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Pitched natural slate roof to extensions. Nap rendered walls. Limestone roughly dressed walls and nap rendered walls to extension. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills and red brick surrounds. Timber panelled door. Roughcast rendered boundary wall with cast-metal gates.

NAME: Priory
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1805, with two-bay three-storey extension to east in 1913 and two-storey extension to north in 1954. Now in use as priory. Pitched natural slate roof with cement rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Flat roof to extension to north, pitched roof to rear extensions, and hipped roof to porch. Painted roughcast rendered walls with moulded cornices, cement render plinth and quoins. Timber sliding sash windows with render surrounds and concrete sills. Top hung outward opening timber windows to rear. Timber glazed door with top and sidelights. Metal grilles to ground floor openings. uPVC glazed doors and bow window to rear. Roughcast rubble boundary walls with red brick former gateway. Profiled metal single and double leaf gates with rubble stone piers. Grounds contain archaeological carved stone fragments from Dominican Abbey formerly located at Abbey Street.

NAME: Holy Cross Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding gable-fronted eight-bay neo-Gothic Roman Catholic church with nave, side aisles and steeple to north east corner, built c. 1870, and with side chapel to west, built c. 1940. Pitched green slate roof with wrought-iron cross finials and cast-iron rain water goods. Roughly dressed snecked red sandstone walls with ashlar string courses and buttresses to side elevations with feathered ashlar skews. Leaded stained glass in ashlar sandstone tracery with ashlar hood mouldings and protective exterior glazing. Timber matchboard doors with ornate wrought-iron hinges in deeply recessed lancet arched opening with ashlar limestone surround. Carved tympanum over paired entrance doors to nave with green marble dividing collonnette. Rose window to north entrance front. Snecked rubble sandstone wall to south. Ashlar decoratively carved collonnette and holy water font to north of entrance survive from a medieval building. Spire contemplated but not completed. Patron was Bishop Benedict David Moriarty of Kerry, Dominican Church;  Dominican Provincial, Very Rev.  B. T.  Russell.  Prior Very Rev.  T. R.  Rush and Chair of UDC, Henry J. Donovan. Designed by Ashlin & Pugin.

NAME: Irish Nationwide
COMPOSITION: Terraced-two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1845, now in use as bank with beauty salon to upper floors. Pitched artificial slate roof with galvanised gutter, uPVC downpipe, and having decorative cornice below roof level. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with metal tie bar plate above first floor openings. Timber sliding sash windows with moulded reveals and mouldings to upper floors. Timber fixed windows and timber glazed and timber panelled doors with fanlights to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront on limestone plinth. Tiled entrance to porch area.

NAME: Kelly's The Mall Pharmacy
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c.1855, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched bracketed artificial slate roof with projecting moulded cornice to parapet. Painted cement rendered walls with platband at sill level to second floor. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows with moulded reveals and surrounds to upper floors. Timber fixed window and timber glazed door to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: Vero Moda
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1885, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with uPVC rainwater goods. Roughcast rendered walls with platband at sill level and having channelled rendered walls to ground floor. Paired timber sliding sash windows with moulded decorative render surrounds to upper floors. Modern glazed shopfront c. 2002.

NAME: Elvery's / Charlie Nelligan's / A- Wear
COMPOSITION: Attached five-bay three-storey Edwardian former department store, built 1907, now in use as three retail outlets.  Pitched artificial slate roof with projecting parapet. Red brick walls with terracotta decorative panels between first and second floor and extensive terracotta detailing to parapet. Cement rendered walls to gable. Timber fixed and top hung outward opening windows with red brick moulded mullions and reveals. Two-storey oriel window to central bay of upper floors. Timber fixed windows and timber glazed doors to ground floor with painted shop signs above.

NAME: Presbytery
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built 1884, with ingle-bay three-storey annex. Projecting canted full height gabled bay window to rear. Now in use as presbytery. Pitched double-span artificial slate roof with red brick chimneystack, polygonal clayware pots, uPVC gutter and cast-iron down pipe. Painted cement rendered walls with mutules to eaves and continuous hood mouldings to ground floor. Timber sliding sash windows in pointed shallow segmental-arched openings with moulded reveals. Metal cast-iron grilles to ground floor windows. Timber panelled door with toplight. Boot scrape to right hand side of front door.

NAME: Presbytery
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey presbytery, built 1963, with three-storey return to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with uPVC gutter and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls with continuous hood moulding to ground floor. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills to upper floors. Timber sliding sash windows in pointed segmental-arched openings to ground floor.

NAME: Kingdom Travel / World Choice
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1790, now in use as offices, with shop to ground floor. Pitched double-span caulked natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows and aluminium glazed door to ground floor, also timber panelled door with toplight surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: Pat Meehan
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1810, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with galvanised rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with painted stone sills to first floor. Timber sliding sash windows to second floor. Timber fixed windows leading to recessed timber glazed door surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor. Carved detailing to shopfront brackets. Tiles to porch area.

NAME: Naughton's
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1815, having three-storey extension to rear with single-pitched two-storey extension adjoining. Now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and galvanised gutter. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with moulded render panel between first and second floor. Cement rendered walls to extension. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window and timber glazed door with top and margin lights to ground floor surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Detailed carving to shopfront bracket. uPVC top hung outward opening windows and timber sliding sash windows to extension.

NAME: Lee Records/Rusk Dry Cleaners
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay three-storey with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1830, now in use as retail outlets. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls with marble cladding and painted mosaic tesserae to ground floor. Cement rendered walls to rear. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to second floor, concrete sills to first floor. Fixed timber windows and timber glazed doors to ground floor with timber shop signs above. Boarded openings to rear. Rubble stone and concrete outbuilding with cement rendered chimneystack.

NAME: Bank of Ireland
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over basement former house, built 1837, now in use as bank. Pavilions and first floor projecting bay added c. 1925. Pitched double-span purple slate roof with corniced projecting parapet to frontage, and having balustraded flat roofs to pavilions. Painted nap rendered walls with render quoins. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed windows surrounded by moulded archivolts to ground floor. uPVC glazed door and fixed windows to pavilions. Timber panelled door with radial fanlight and moulded archivolt to ground floor. Granite steps and brick paving to entrance. Cast-iron railings on painted stone plinths with wrought-iron lantern stands.

NAME: Allegro Restaurant
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace two-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1830, with single-storey extension to rear. Now in use as restaurant. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with uPVC rainwater goods and cornice below roof level. Flat roof to extension. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins. Roughcast rendered walls to rear. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with painted stone sills, moulded window surrounds and label mouldings. Fixed timber windows, timber half glazed double leaf doors with toplights and timber panelled door to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Tesserae (mosaic tiles) to entrance porch. Fire escape to rear.

NAME: Kennelly's Pharmacy
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1830, with single-storey extension to rear. Now in use as retail outlet. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with uPVC gutter. Flat roof to extension. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with projecting canopy to first floor and projecting metal bracket with shop sign. Marble cladding to ground floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills and moulded reveals to upper floors. Aluminium fixed window and glazed door to ground floor. Timber glazed door to access upper stories.

NAME: Hurley's
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1830, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with galvanised rainwater goods. Cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills to upper floors. Fixed timber windows leading back to half glazed timber double leaf doors with toplights and aluminium glazed door with toplight to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront with carved detailing. Carved detailing to shopfront brackets.

NAME: John Ross Jeweller
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay four-storey former house, built c. 1830, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with cast-iron gutter. Painted cement rendered walls with projecting clock sign. Timber sliding sash windows and painted concrete sills to second and third floors. Timber top hung outward opening windows to first floor. Timber fixed windows leading back to timber half glazed door to ground floor, surrounded by pilaster and entablature shopfront with carved detailing.

NAME: The Pikeman
COMPOSITION: Limestone statue of pike man on limestone and marble plinth, built 1938, with memorial plaques, limestone pediment and marble columns to each side. Base inscribed 'O Brien Castleisland 1995'. Memorial erected to commemorate the various risings in Ireland against British Rule. Destroyed c. 1920, rebuilt c. 1938, moved c. 1975 and c. 1995 to accommodate building and renovation of culvert below.  Marble from Castleisland and limestone from Ballybeggan were used in the original c. 1905 monument. Limestone curbing to surrounding paving.

NAME: Paddy Power
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1850, now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods, projecting cornice and parapet. Painted cement rendered walls with moulded platband at sill level second floor. Moulded window reveals and surrounds. Top hung outward opening windows with concrete sills to upper floors. Fixed timber window and timber panel glazed door to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront with plastic sign above.

NAME: Country Pork
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1850, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with projecting cornice and parapet. Painted cement rendered walls with moulded plat course at sill level second floor and having moulded window surrounds and reveals. Timber top hung outward opening windows and timber sliding sash windows to upper floors. Fixed timber windows and glazed timber door to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Timber panelled door with toplight to access upper floors.

NAME: Jess Mc Carthy
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace three-bay three-storey house, built c. 1820, now also in use as public house. Pitched double-span artificial caulked slate roof with roughcast rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with roughcast rendered walls to side wall. Timber top hung outward opening window with painted stone sills, concrete sills to side wall. Fixed shop window and timber panelled doors with toplights surrounded by finely carved timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Timber matchboard door to side wall. Two-storey outbuilding to rear with corrugated-metal sheet roof.

NAME: John J. O Connor
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1900, with attic accommodation. Now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rooflights. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with cornice to parapet. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window and recessed timber glazed door to ground floor with painted timber shop sign above, capped by cast-iron cresting.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1800. Pitched purple slate roof with red brick cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with projecting eaves course. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullions to first floor. Timber sliding sash windows to ground floor all with painted stone sills. Timber matchboard front door.

Terraced three-bay three-storey house with integral carriageway, built 1893. Pitched caulked natural slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron gutter. Painted cement render over coursed rubble stone walls with brick dressings to openings and with render platbands at sill levels. Timber sliding sash windows with moulded sills and render pediments to upper floors. Timber fixed window with metal grille and timber panelled door with toplight to ground floor. Timber garage doors to carriageway.

Terraced three-bay two-storey with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1885, with integral carriageway. Two-storey extension to rear. Now in use as flats. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods and having cast-iron rooflight to rear pitch. Flat roof to extension. Snecked sandstone and limestone walls with limestone string course at sill level first floor. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills, red bricked reveals and flat arches. Timber panelled door with toplight. Timber matchboard double leaf doors to school entrance. Limestone steps to entrances. Single-storey timber-clad shed to rear with single-pitched roof behind mass concrete wall, built c. 1920. Corrugated-iron clad outbuilding to rear of site.

NAME: Solar
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1840, now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with red brick and nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window and timber glazed door with metal grilles to ground floor. Timber panelled door to ground floor with painted shop sign above.

NAME: O' Neills Pharmacy
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace two-bay three-storey former house, built 1903, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof, hipped to corner, with cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with wall mounted pharmacy signs. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window and timber half glazed door with toplight to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Windows contain stained glass.

NAME: Franks Fast Food
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1880, now also in use as restaurant. Pitched caulked natural slate roof with red brick chimneystack, uPVC rainwater goods, painted metal sheet to dormer and decorative timber eaves board. Painted nap rendered walls having projecting metal bracket with painted timber sign. Label moulding to first floor window. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Fixed timber window with timber half glazed door surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor. Built as pair with number 16 Upper Castle Street.

Terraced single-bay two-storey house with dormer attic, built c. 1880, now vacant. Pitched caulked natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods, metal sheet to dormer and having decorative eaves board. Painted nap rendered walls with projecting metal bracket for shop sign having painted brick to ground floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Label moulding to first floor window. Fixed timber window with timber half glazed door having painted timber shop sign above to ground floor. Built as pair with number 17 Upper Castle Street.

Terraced single-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1850, until recently in use as retail outlet. Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete barging to party wall, nap rendered chimneystack and galvanised gutter. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls. Paired six-over-six pane timber sliding sash windows with dividing timber mullion and painted concrete sills to upper floors. Fixed timber window with metal grille and timber panelled door with toplight to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Security alarm attached to first floor window mullion.

Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1850, formerly used as retail outlet. Pitched caulked artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods and concrete barging to party wall. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Paired timber sliding sash windows with timber dividing mullions and painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window with metal grille and timber glazed panelled door with toplight to ground floor, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront.

NAME: Presentation Primary School
COMPOSITION: Arched entrance gateway with piers and entablature, built 1874, leading to school. Painted red brick walls with limestone plinth string courses and key stones, brick mutules to entablature, and nap render above arch. Cast-iron double leaf gates to arch.

NAME: St. John's Roman Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding neo-Gothic Roman Catholic church with ten-bay nave elevations, side aisles, side chapels and spire to north, built 1861, renovated and extended 1950-1960. Designed by J.J. Mc Carthy and George Ashlin (spire designer). Pitched purple slate roof with single-pitched roofs to side aisles, limestone ashlar to spire, limestone pinnacles and bellcote lucarnes. Snecked red sandstone walls with ashlar limestone quoins and string courses. Leaded stained glass in ashlar limestone tracery, single/double/triple lancets and trefoils. Timber matchboard doors with ornate wrought-iron hinges in pointed arch openings with ashlar limestone surrounds. Brick pavements, wrought-iron railings and rubble limestone boundary walls to site. Roughcast rendered wall to car park. Statue of Virgin and Child and fifteenth-century carving of Assumption to site. Limestone piers with skew coping and cast metal railings to main entrance. Graveyard with memorial stones including carved Celtic cross. Cut stone piers and reveals of former building to west of church set in snecked dressed limestone wall. Stained glass by Michael O Connor in 1861, stations of the cross by Sean Keating, stained glass window inserted 1957, by Richard Icing and Patrick Pollen.

NAME: Presentation Convent Chapel
COMPOSITION: Attached five-bay neo-Gothic chapel with semi octagonal chapel end and transepts, built 1914, with two-bay nun's choir to west adjoining St. John's Church. Designed by Samuel Hynes. Pitched purple slate roof with limestone gable copings, gablets to each facet of chancel, cross stepped gable with bell cote and cast-iron rainwater goods. Limestone mutules to eaves course with gablets to faceted chancel end. Snecked rubble sandstone walls with limestone quoins and string courses, having inset fragment of carved stone from former Dominican Friary. Leaded stained glass windows in limestone ashlar lancets with hood mouldings and in trefoil openings. Rose window to north transept. Timber matchboard double leaf doors with wrought-iron hinges set in lancet arched openings with limestone surrounds, hood mouldings and limestone steps. Glass house to rear. Cemetery to south with cast-iron grave markers.

NAME: Presentation Convent
COMPOSITION: Attached thirteen-bay three-storey with attic accommodation convent, built c. 1915, with projecting gabled bays to centre and terminating ends. Pitched purple slate roof with cast-iron rooflights, cast-iron rainwater goods, limestone and sandstone ashlar chimneystacks and having limestone dentils to eaves. Snecked red sandstone walls with limestone ashlar quoins and string courses. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone moulded surrounds, sills and reveals, set in lancet arches to ground floor and second floor. Timber panelled glazed double leaf doors with glazed lancet arch above and flanking lancets. Timber panelled, glazed and matchboard doors. Limestone steps to doors. Wrought-iron railings to exterior basement entrance. Glass house and outbuildings to right hand side. Roughcast rendered boundary walls. Garden to south.

NAME: Presentation Primary School
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay two-storey school, built 1874, with single-bay two-storey projection bay added c. 1905, five-bay two-storey extension to left hand side (west) and four-bay two-storey extension to rear (north) added c. 1950. Pitched purple slate roof with limestone barging to gable walls, red brick chimneystack and nap rendered chimneystack. Hipped artificial slate roof to projecting bay. Pitched artificial slate roof to left hand side and rear extensions with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted roughcast rendered walls with nap render plinth and red brick quoins. Timber bottom-hung inward-opening windows with painted brick surrounds and stone sills. Single/paired/tripartite timber sliding sash windows with concrete mullions, cement render surrounds and continuous sills. Timber matchboard door with concrete canopy. Concrete step to door. School yard to rear with cast-metal gates and roughcast rendered walls set in rubble stone boundary wall c. 1915.

NAME: Presentation Primary School
COMPOSITION: Attached six-bay single-storey school annex, built 1936. Pitched purple slate roof with limestone coping, cross finial and cast-iron rainwater goods. Snecked ashlar sandstone walls with limestone quoins and string course. Limestone recess to gable with statue. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills and reveals. Timber glazed double leaf doors with mosaic above, set in pointed lancet arch.

NAME: Presentation Primary School
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay single-storey school, built 1936, around central courtyard with projecting terminating gables to either end of elevation and having central fleche. Hipped pitched purple slate roof with limestone coping, cross finials, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber eaves boards and having copper clad timber fleche to centre of roof. Snecked sandstone walls with ashlar limestone quoins, limestone recessed arch with statue to front, carved lintels to side and rear and having medallions to gables. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone mullions and reveals. Timber matchboard double leaf doors with limestone steps. Carved limestone altar on tiled plinth to front façade

NAME: Christian Brothers School
COMPOSITION: Detached fourteen-bay two-storey school, built 1927, having five-bay single-storey projection and gabled wings to park front. Two-storey extension to right hand side. Pitched natural slate roof with limestone copings, cast-iron gutters, uPVC down pipes, domed ventilator to centre of pitch and limestone cornice. Snecked ashlar sandstone walls with limestone plinth, limestone string course to central bay and carved limestone plaques to gables. uPVC bottom-hung inward-opening windows with limestone sills and raised reveals. Timber panelled doors with toplight and limestone surround. uPVC glazed double leaf doors to extension. Cast-iron railings and concrete steps with cast metal railings to site.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half-dormer windows, ground floor canted bay window and entrance canopy to front. Pitched purple slate roof having brick chimneystack, bargeboards to dormers, cast-iron rainwater goods, and with single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to bay window. Painted roughcast rendered walls to upper floors, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber panelled door with fanlight and timber top-hung outward-opening lights to bay window to ground floor. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone to boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Walsh & Associates
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half-dormer windows, canted bay window and entrance canopy to front. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with red bricked chimneystack, bargeboards to dormers, cast-iron rainwater goods, and having single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to bay window. Painted roughcast rendered walls to upper floors, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at first floor sill level. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber sliding sash bay window and timber panelled door with fanlight to ground floor. uPVC bottom-hung inward opening windows to rear. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half-dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack, decorative bargeboards to dormers, cast-iron rainwater goods, and having single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to bay window. Painted roughcast rendered walls to upper floors, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber sliding sash bay window to ground floor. Timber panelled door with fanlight. uPVC bottom-hung inward-opening windows to rear. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Quirke Security
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods, and having decorative bargeboards to single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof canopy. Painted roughcast rendered walls to upper floors, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber sliding sash bay window to ground floor. Timber panelled door with toplight. Nap rendered pier and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Carl's Townhouse
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half-dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Now in use as guest house. Pitched artificial slate roof with decorative bargeboards to dormers, cement rendered chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods and having single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to canopy. Roughcast rendered walls to upper floors, rubble stone to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber top-hung outward-opening opening lights to bay window to ground floor. Timber panelled door with toplight. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Peevers and Slye
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built 1899, with two-storey extension to rear, gabled half dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with bargeboards to gabled dormer, cast-iron rainwater goods, nap rendered brick chimneystack and having single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to canopy. Painted roughcast rendered walls to upper floors, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. uPVC top-hung outward-opening opening lights to bay windows to ground floor. Timber panelled door with fanlight. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Pitched artificial slate roof with red brick chimneystack, decorative bargeboard, cast-iron rainwater goods and having single-pitched artificial slate roof to porch. Painted roughcast rendered walls, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber sliding sash bay window to ground floor. Timber panelled door with fanlight. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Greenview House
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built 1899, with two-storey split-level return to rear, gabled half-dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Pitched artificial slate roof with bargeboards to dormers, cast-iron rainwater goods and having single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to porch. Painted roughcast rendered walls, cement rendered walls to ground floor with string course at sill level first floor. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted brick sills and surrounds. Timber top-hung outward-opening opening lights to bay window to ground floor. Timber panelled door with toplight. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house, built 1899, with split-level two-storey return to rear, gabled half-dormer windows and canted bay window and entrance canopy to ground floor frontage. Pitched natural slate roof with roughcast rendered chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods and having single-pitched hipped artificial slate roof to canopy. Painted roughcast rendered walls. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows. Timber panelled door with toplight. uPVC top-hung outward-opening lights to bay window to ground floor. Nap rendered piers and cast-iron railings. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

End-of-terrace single-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1810. Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete barging to party walls, cement rendered chimneystack and uPVC gutter. Painted cement rendered walls with render quoins. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted concrete sills. Timber panelled door with toplight. Stone steps with wrought-iron railings to front door. Limestone rubble boundary wall to rear. Derelict former outbuilding to rear.

NAME: Antiques
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation house, built c. 1810, now also in use as retail outlet. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rooflights, cast-iron rainwater goods and cement rendered chimneystack. Painted cement rendered walls with projecting metal bracket having painted timber shop sign. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted concrete sills. Timber panelled door c. 1810 flanked by Ionic engaged columns with carved lintel and plain fanlight above surrounded by moulded archivolt. Timber panelled door to basement. Concrete steps with cast- and wrought-iron railings to front door. Single-storey outbuilding to rear.

NAME: Restaurant Uno
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1810, now with restaurant to basement and rear of ground floor. Pitched natural slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls with render quoins, plat bands at sill levels and channelled rendered walls to basement. Timber top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with moulded nap render surrounds. Timber panelled door c. 1810, with plain fanlight above and moulded surround. Stone steps with wrought-iron railings up to front door. Two-storey outbuilding to rear in use as kitchen.

Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation house, built c. 1810. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack, cast-iron rooflight and rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls with render quoins, channelled rendered walls to basement and having plat band between basement and first floor. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullions, painted stone sills and moulded surrounds. uPVC bottom-hung inward-opening window to entrance level. Recessed timber panelled door c. 1810, with toplight and moulded render surround. Limestone steps and wrought-iron railings c. 1970 up to front door.

End-of-terrace single-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1805. Pitched double-span artificial slate roof with concrete barging to party wall and cement rendered chimneystack. Painted cement rendered walls with render quoins and having channelled rendered walls to basement. Paired timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills and moulded render surrounds. Aluminium glazed door with side and toplights. Timber sliding sash windows to rear. Limestone steps and wrought-iron railings up to front door.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation house, built c. 1835, with three-storey extension and single-storey extension to rear. Pitched caulked natural slate roof having slate hung chimneystack with concrete barging to party wall, cast-iron rooflights and cast-iron rainwater goods. Flat roof to single-storey extension. Painted cement rendered walls with slate roof cladding to rear. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight. Timber top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening window to ground floor. Single and tripartite timber sliding sash windows to extension. Timber top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward -opening windows to single-storey extension. Limestone steps and wrought-iron railings to front door. Cement rendered boundary walls with timber gate to rear.

Terraced two-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1835, three-storey extension to rear.  Now in use as flats. Pitched natural slate roof with natural slate hung cladding to chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Single-pitched roof to extension. Painted cement rendered walls. Roughcast rendered walls and natural slate cladding to extension. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills to second floor. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to first floor. Timber top-hung outward-opening window to ground floor with painted limestone sills. Boarded and grille to basement opening. Limestone steps and wrought-iron railings up to front door. Cement rendered boundary wall and timber gate to rear.

NAME: Vals Taverns Ltd.
COMPOSITION: Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1820, with single- and two-storey extensions to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights, cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls with natural slate cladding to gable wall left hand side. Rubble stone and cement rendered walls to extension. Timber sliding sash tripartite windows with limestone sills and cast metal railings. Timber panelled door flanked by limestone engaged Ionic columns with carved lintel and radial fanlight above having carved archivolt with shell motif. Timber sliding sash windows to rear. Limestone steps with wrought-iron railings to front door. Cement rendered boundary wall and timber gate to rear.

Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation house, built c. 1815, with two-storey extensions to rear. Pitched caulked natural slate roof having nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Tall brick chimneystack to extension to rear. Cement rendered walls. Timber sliding sash tripartite windows with moulded surrounds and limestone sills. Timber panelled door flanked by carved limestone pilasters with carved lintel and radial fanlight above surrounded by moulded archivolt. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows to rear. Canted bay window to first floor of extension.

NAME: Quayside House
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1820, now in use as offices and annexed to building adjoining to right hand side. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted roughcast rendered walls with limestone plinth. Timber sliding sash windows with raised render reveals and painted stone sills. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullion and having metal grille to ground floor.

NAME: Quayside House
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1820, now in use as offices, annexed to building adjoining to left hand side. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted roughcast rendered walls with limestone plinth. Timber sliding sash windows with raised render reveals and painted stone sills. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullion, and having metal grille to ground floor. Timber panelled door with radial fanlight and moulded render surround.
Wrought-iron railings on cut limestone plinth with iron bollard to gate, built c. 1795. Railings originally separated Day Place from unculverted Big River which flowed to south-east.

NAME: Tralee Gas Supplies
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited seven-bay five-storey former warehouse, built c. 1835, now in use as retail outlet and workshops. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Limestone rubble walls with ashlar quoins, having cement rendered walls to ground floor with painted metal and plastic shop-signs. Fixed timber windows/boarded/blocked windows with red brick flat arches and slate sills. Blocked-up elliptical-arched former opening. Fixed timber window and timber glazed door to ground floor of gable end.

Formerly terraced, now corner-sited three-bay three-storey house, built c. 1820. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack. Painted cement rendered walls. Paired and single timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Timber panelled door.

NAME: Maris Stella
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey former pair of houses, built c. 1800, with semi-detached single-storey building containing two single garages to right hand side. Pitched caulked natural slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and galvanised rainwater goods. Corrugated-aluminium roofs to garages. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Roughcast rendered to side wall. Painted nap rendered walls to garages. Timber sliding sash windows with painted concrete sills. Timber panelled door. Timber fixed window to ground floor. Enamelled corrugated-aluminium doors to garages.

Terraced two-bay single-storey former carriage house, built c. 1810, with elliptical arch having dressed stone voussoirs to carriageway entrance. Now in use as store. Pitched corrugated-iron sheet roof with concrete barging to party walls. Rubble limestone walls. Blocked archway with dressed rubble stone voussoirs and projecting pierced hinge restraining stone. Blocked doorway with timber lintel.

Terraced three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820, with extensive stucco decoration. Pitched artificial slate roof having nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with moulded render vermiculated quoins and astylar stucco decorative architraves to openings. Single and paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing timber mullions and painted stone sills. Timber panelled door c. 1880.

Terraced three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and uPVC rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Single and paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullions and painted limestone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1820. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls to ground floor. Exposed rubble stone to first floor façade with raised concrete platband at first floor string course. Single and paired timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight.

End-of-terrace eight-bay two-storey former school, built 1884, with single- and two-storey extensions to rear. Now in use as workshop. Pitched natural slate roof with sandstone and limestone ashlar chimneystacks and having cast-iron rainwater goods. Single-pitched natural slate roof to single-storey extension. Flat roof to two-storey extension. Roughcast rendered walls to upper area with cement rendered walls below. Red bricked and limestone construction to nap rendered gable wall. Rubble limestone and sandstone to rear. Timber sliding sash windows in pointed segmental-arched openings with metal grilles to ground floor. Timber panelled door with toplight set in lancet arched opening with sidelights having limestone surrounds. Timber panelled door with timber panel above. Single and tripartite timber sliding sash windows to rear with red brick surrounds and limestone sills. Galvanised double leaf doors to rear. Timber matchboard door to single-storey extension. Limestone step to entrance. Double leaf cast metal gates leading to rear. Rubble stone wall to rear.

Detached six-bay two-storey former house, built c. 1820, converted to convent and extended c. 1885, with polygonal projection to left hand side. Pitched double-span hipped artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods, red brick chimneystack, natural slate roof to chapel, and mansard roof to rear. Painted nap rendered walls. uPVC bottom-hung inward-opening windows set in segmental-arched openings. Timber panelled door with top and margin lights. Lancet windows to polygonal projection. Limestone rubble boundary wall with cast-metal railings. Limestone steps to front door. Wrought-iron gate and statue of St. Joseph to front garden.

Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, now vacant. Pitched natural slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Cement rendered walls. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullion and stone sill to second floor. Timber top-hung outward-opening window and timber sliding sash window to ground floor, both with stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight. Blocked opening to basement. Limestone steps to front door.

Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1800, now in use as flats. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflight and uPVC gutter. Cement rendered walls to ground floor with natural slate cladding to upper floors. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Metal grille to basement window. Timber glazed door with toplight. Limestone steps to front door.

Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1800, now in use as flats. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflight, uPVC gutter, cast-iron down pipe and cement rendered chimneystack. Cement rendered walls to ground floor with natural slate cladding to upper floors. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Metal grille to basement window. Timber glazed door with toplight. Limestone steps to front door.

End-of-terrace single-bay three-storey over basement with attic accommodation house, built c. 1800, now in use as flats. Pitched artificial slate roof with toplight and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls to ground floor, with natural slate cladding to upper floors. Rendered walls to gable wall. Paired uPVC window with limestone sills to upper floors. uPVC window to ground floor with painted limestone sill. uPVC bottom-hung inward opening window with metal grille to basement. Timber panelled door with toplight. Limestone steps to front door.

NAME: Excise Bonded Warehouse
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited four-bay two-storey warehouse, built c. 1830, roof replaced c. 1975 and having two-storey extension to rear. Pitched corrugated-sheet roof with toplight and uPVC rainwater goods. Rubble stone walls with cement rendered walls to rear. Exposed mass concrete and concrete block to gable. Boarded windows with metal bars. Timber matchboard double leaf doors.

NAME: Kerry School of Music
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited formerly detached five-bay two-storey over basement former house, built c. 1810, with single and two-storey extensions to rear. Formerly used as custom house, now in use as music school. Pitched and hipped natural slate roof. Flat roof to single-storey extension. Nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted moulded stone sills. Timber panelled double leaf doors with moulded limestone lintel having radial fanlight above surrounded by moulded limestone archivolt supported on limestone pilasters. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows with concrete sills to basement. Concrete steps to front door. Rubble stone boundary wall with limestone plinth and cast-iron railings.

NAME: Val O Shea's
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1865, three-storey extension to rear. Now in use as public house. Pitched artificial slate roof to main roof and extension, hipped to east. Painted cement rendered walls with natural slate cladding between first floor and second floor openings and having projecting metal street lights. Roughcast rendered to gable wall. Paired timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted concrete sills to upper floors. Timber tripartite fixed windows with decoratively carved frames to ground floor. Timber panelled single and double leaf doors with toplights, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. uPVC top-hung out-ward opening windows to extension.

NAME: The Cookery
COMPOSITION: Pair of terraced single-bay three-storey former houses, built c. 1860, now united and in use as restaurant. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with roughcast rendered to gable wall. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullions and painted stone sills to upper floors. Paired timber top-hung outward-opening window with painted stone sill to ground floor. Timber panelled door with toplight.

Terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1870, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and uPVC rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with moulded render medallion to upper floors, stucco dentilled cornice to entablature and having shop sign over ground floor. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted concrete sills and moulded render surrounds. Timber panelled glazed door to ground floor with moulded render stucco surrounds. Timber fixed window to shopfront.

NAME: The Original Gem
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited terraced two-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1870, now in use as retail outlet. Pitched natural slate roof with uPVC rainwater goods. Painted cement rendered walls with decorative stucco dentilled cornice to shop sign entablature. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted concrete sills and moulded surrounds. Timber fixed window and timber glazed door with toplight all flanked by moulded render pilasters and entablatures.

Terraced single-bay three-storey house, built c. 1810, with two-storey return to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Single and pitched purple slate roofs to rear and return. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Paired uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills. Venetian style window opening to first floor. Timber panelled door with radial fanlight above. Timber panelled door with toplight. Arched window to stairs to rear. Limestone steps and concrete steps to doors. Two-storey outbuilding to rear of site with pitched slated roof and nap rendered walls.

NAME: St. Joseph's Guesthouse
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey with attic accommodation former house, built c. 1815, now in use as guesthouse. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron gutter and having dormer windows to rear pitch. Painted cement rendered walls. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills. Timber panelled door with radial fanlight c. 1980 and moulded archivolt surround. Concrete steps to front door.

Terraced single-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1825, formerly with return to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with rubble limestone wall to rear. uPVC bottom-hung inward-opening windows with concrete sills. Timber panelled door. Boarded opening to basement. Boarded and grilled openings to rear. Limestone steps to front door. Remains of former two-storey mews buildings to rear, now unroofed.

Terraced gable-fronted six-bay two-storey warehouse, built c. 1875. Pitched tarred metal sheet roof. Snecked limestone walls to ground floor with limestone string course above. Roughcast rendered walls to first floor. Roughcast rendered and rubble stone to side wall. Fixed timber segmental-arched windows with limestone reveals and sills, having keystones to first floor. Fixed timber windows and glazed double leaf doors in segmental-arched openings to ground floor.

NAME: Tralee Superbowl
COMPOSITION: Attached seven-bay two-storey former hall, built 1908, with projecting central bay and having terracotta brick render detailing to façade. Now in use as bowling alley. Pitched profiled metal cladding to roof with red brick parapet projecting to central bay with terracotta detailing. Painted brick plinth, channelled nap rendered walls to ground floor, nap rendered walls to first floor with render quoins, and having string courses to sill level ground floor and floor level first floor. Timber sliding sash windows with render surrounds and continuous sills to first floor. Timber sliding sash windows set in arches to ground floor. Timber panelled single and double leaf doors with fanlights. Limestone steps up to entrance doors. Building was also known as 'County Hall' but burned in 1920. Used as a cinema in the 1930's (presumably after renovation) and by Siamsa Tire as theatre in 1980's.

NAME: O' Keefe Insurances Ltd.,
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-story former house, built c. 1830, now in use as offices and flats. Pitched artificial slate roof with uPVC and cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled cement rendered walls. Single and tripartite timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window with painted stone sill and timber glazed door with margin and toplights to ground floor, with painted timber shop sign.  Timber panelled door with toplight giving access to upper floor.

NAME: Hibernian Insurance
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1830, with single-storey extension to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched hipped artificial slate roof with uPVC rainwater goods. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights to extension. Painted cement rendered walls with limestone plinth, having natural slate cladding in panels between openings. Timber sliding sash tripartite windows with limestone sills. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with moulded lintel, radial fanlight and moulded archivolt above, flanked by ashlar Ionic columns.

Semi-detached two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1830, with central window to party wall and projecting single-storey porch, renovated c. 1992. Pitched artificial slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack. Limestone plinth with cement rendered walls to ground floor and having natural slate cladding to upper floors. Paired timber sliding sash windows with dividing mullions and limestone sills. Timber panelled door.

NAME: Bella Pia
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited semi-detached two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1830, with central window to party wall and projecting single-storey porch. Now also in use as restaurant with two-storey extension to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Flat roof to extension. Painted cement rendered walls with painted shop sign having natural slate cladding to upper floors. Paired timber sliding sash windows and paired uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows. Timber sliding sash windows and uPVC top-hung outward-opening window with limestone sills. Timber panelled door and timber glazed door with toplight to ground floor.

NAME: Town Park
COMPOSITION: Wrought-iron railings to plinth wall of Town Park with concrete coping and ashlar piers c. 1925. Wrought-iron gates. Later wrought-iron railings to adjacent Pairc an Phiarsaigh and rubble stone and timber benches c. 1972.

NAME: Ashe Memorial Hall
COMPOSITION: Detached thirteen-bay three-storey former Local Authority offices, built c. 1925, with five-bay three-storey over basement breakfront entrance facing Denny Street. Now in use as museum and offices. Hipped natural slate roof with snecked sandstone ashlar chimneystack and galvanised rainwater goods. Snecked sandstone ashlar walls with painted stone plinth, string course between ground floor and first floor, projecting cornice to second floor and third floor, channelled sandstone walls to basement to front (north) elevation, and having pilasters and entablature to central five-bay breakfront. Metal side-hung pivot windows with moulded painted stone sills and surrounds. Timber matchboard glazed double leaf doors with moulded stucco surround to main entrance. Concrete steps with railing and stucco candelabras to piers to main entrance. Cast-metal railings to site. Building commenced 1924 and completed 1928.  Building is designed to be seen in the round and closes vista at end of Denny Street.
Rubble limestone boundary wall with segmental-arch opening, built c. 1830.

NAME: ACC Bank
COMPOSITION: Attached four-bay two-storey former Weslyan meeting house, built c. 1810, to rear of street building. Later used as Chamber of Commerce, renovated c. 1990 and now annexed to bank. Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete gable coping, projecting ashlar eaves course and uPVC rainwater goods. Rooflights added c. 1990. Cement rendered walls. Pointed arch window openings with uPVC replacement windows.

NAME: James H. North & Co.
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1805, with converted attic and two-storey return to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with rooflights. Painted nap rendered walls with quoins to upper storeys. Timber shopfront to ground floor. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with stone sills and raised moulded nap rendered surrounds to upper floors. Timber fixed windows with recessed glazing to timber panelled door surrounded by recent timber pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor.

NAME: Pikeman Bar, Grand Hotel
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1810, with limestone façade to ground floor. Now in use as public house, annexed to hotel to south (right hand side) in 1965. Pitched double-span artificial slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Channelled ashlar walls with free standing Ionic columns and entablature to ground floor. Painted nap rendered walls above. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows with stone sills and moulded surrounds to upper floors. uPVC projecting bay window with top hung outward opening windows having timber panelling below to ground floor. Timber panelled doors with carved limestone lintels. Limestone doorstep.

NAME: Grand Hotel
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1810. Later used as post office from 1887 to 1910, now in use as hotel. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with projecting parapet cornice and cement rendered chimneystack. Painted nap rendered walls to upper floors, projecting string cornice at sill level on third floor. Channelled rendered walls with moulded string cornice at sill and arch spring level with limestone entablature at ground floor level. Projecting wrought-iron bracket and timber sign to first floor. Projecting metal arched canopy over front door. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows with moulded surrounds to upper storeys. Decorative stucco pediment to first floor windows. uPVC bottom hung inward opening arched windows to ground floor with moulded archivolt surrounds. Timber panelled double leaf door with fanlight. Limestone doorstep.

NAME: Grand Hotel, Samuel's
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1810, now in use as hotel. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with timber name sign to ground floor. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills and moulded render surrounds. uPVC windows to ground floor. Glazed timber panelled door with fanlight above, surrounded by limestone pilasters and lintel with carved archivolt over fanlight, having limestone doorstep.

NAME: Brian T. Foley, Optometrist
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over house, built c. 1835, with three-storey return. Now also in use as surgery. Pitched natural slate roof. Nap rendered walls. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with fanlight and moulded archivolt, approached by limestone steps. Wrought-iron railings on limestone plinth. Two-storey outbuilding to rear.

NAME: Sherry Fitzgerald O' Connell
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1810, now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with cement rendered chimneystacks having polygonal clayware pots and uPVC rainwater goods. Painted nap rendered walls with projecting string course at sill level to first floor. Flood light to third floor. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills to ground floor and third floor. Timber panelled door with toplight surrounded by moulded render pilasters and radial stucco decoration. Louvered openings at basement level. Multi-paned timber sliding sash window to stairs half landing. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door.

NAME: Imperial Hotel
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1830, now in use as hotel. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled painted nap rendered walls, having projecting metal bracket with timber sign. Replacement timber sliding sash windows with painted limestone sills and moulded render surrounds. Timber panelled double leaf doors with toplight, having timber pilaster and entablature surround. Limestone steps up to front door. Wrought-iron railings on stone plinth.

NAME: Imperial Hotel
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1830, now in use as hotel. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and polygonal clayware chimneystack pots.
