Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with projecting metal bracket having sign, and with cast render medallion to ground floor. Replacement timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills and moulded render surrounds. Timber panelled double leaf doors flanked by fixed glazing surrounded by pilaster and entablature shopfront. Limestone steps up to front door with cast-iron railings.

NAME: Imperial Hotel
COMPOSITION: Terraced five-bay three-storey former house with integral carriage arch, built c. 1830, now in use as hotel. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins and having timber pilasters and entablature shopfront to ground floor. Aluminium windows with central pivot sections having painted stone sills and moulded render surrounds. Timber sliding sash windows to ground floor. Moulded render surround to elliptical carriageway.

NAME: Royal Liver Assurance
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over former house, built c. 1830, three-storey extension to rear contains dance hall. Formerly used as Co. Kerry Club, now in use as offices. Pitched double-span artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots and limestone cornice. Painted nap rendered walls with moulded quoins to upper floors. Channelled rendered walls to ground floor with limestone string course to sill level first floor and having raised string course below roof cornice. uPVC top hung outward opening windows to upper floors. Stucco entablature and scrolls over windows to first floor openings. Moulded render surrounds with limestone sills to third floor segmental-arched windows with render moulded surrounds. Rusticated ancons to ground floor. Timber panelled door with carved limestone lintel flanked by engaged Ionic columns with radial fanlight and moulded archivolt above. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door.  Retaining interior features.

NAME: Giles Auctioneers
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house c. 1820, with two-storey extension to rear in 1998. Now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with caulking treatment having cast-iron rainwater goods and nap rendered chimneystack. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with projecting metal bracket having timber painted sign. uPVC bottom hung inward opening windows with limestone sills to upper floors. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows to ground floor. Timber panelled door with carved lintel flanked by engaged Ionic columns and margin lights, having radial fanlight above with limestone archivolt. Flush timber door to basement. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door. Concrete steps down to basement.

NAME: Finucane Insurances Ltd.
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1820, with two-storey extension to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted limestone sills. uPVC windows to basement. Timber panelled door with carved entablature and engaged Ionic columns flanked by margin lights with radial fanlight above surrounded by moulded archivolt. Timber panelled door to basement. Cast-iron railings with limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door. Slate flag steps to basement area.

NAME: O' Sullivan Cadogan
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1820, with two-storey extension with double-height atriums c.1990, incorporating former two-storey outhouse to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with rendered chimneystacks. Flat roof to extension with pyramidal rooflight having patent aluminium glazing and polycarbon sheeting translucent panels. Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Top hung outward opening windows to basement. Timber panelled door with carved Ionic engaged columns flanked by margin lights with radial fanlight above surrounded by moulded archivolt. Timber glazed door to basement. Cast-iron railings with limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door. Slate flag steps to basement area.

NAME: Murphy & Sheehy
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1820, with three-storey extension to rear. Formerly used as bank and now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with rendered chimneystack, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls having metal projecting bracket with painted sign. Ashlar quoins to return to rear. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with painted limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved entablature and engaged Ionic columns flanked by margin lights with radial fanlight above surrounded by moulded archivolt. Timber panelled door to basement. Cast-iron railings with limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door. Concrete steps down to basement area.  Reputed to have been a residence of Daniel O Connell.

NAME: Southern Health Board
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1815, with projecting corniced and parapetted roof to front door ground floor. Three-storey extension to rear and plan rearranged 1866. Formerly used as bank and now in use as offices. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with projecting parapet cornice and having chimneystack stack with four octagonal clayware chimney pots. Painted nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins, moulded string cornice below roof cornice, raised string cornice above first floor windows, projecting string cornice at floor level first floor, raised cornice sill level ground floor and having decorative stucco panels flanking front door fanlight arch. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with painted stone sills and having raised render moulded decorative surrounds. Timber panelled door with fanlight above having egg and dart moulding in doorway arch with large keystone. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth. Recessed to former entrance to left hand side.

NAME: Southern Health Board
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace five-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1810, with long two-storey over basement extension to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched and hipped natural slate roof with rendered chimneystack having polygonal clayware pots.  Painted lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls.  Timber sliding sash windows to top floors. Timber top hung outward opening windows to ground floor. Timber fixed windows to basement. Limestone sills. Timber panelled door flanked by engaged Ionic columns with carved lintel and radial fanlight above surrounded by moulded archivolt. Wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth. Rendered steps to front door. Slate flag steps to basement.

Detached two-bay two-storey former gate lodge with gabled porch, built c. 1850, single-storey two-bay extension to rear. Now in use as house. Pitched natural slate roof and carved timber bargeboards to main roof and gabled porch, having nap rendered chimneystacks with clayware pots and cast-iron rainwater goods. Mineralised felt to flat roofed extension. Painted cement rendered walls with limestone plinth. Timber side hung outward opening windows with diamond panes, painted stone sills and label mouldings. Pointed four centred arch with mouldings to porch. Wrought-iron railings to site. Limestone steps to front door, with red clay tiles to porch. Sun dial on stone plinth to rear. Nap rendered boundary wall with concrete coping.

NAME: Finnegan's Holiday Hostel
COMPOSITION: End-of-terrace five-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1826, with two single-storey over basement bay window projections to side (south) wall and three-storey over basement extension to rear c. 1995. Later used as hall and now in use as hostel and restaurant. Pitched and hipped double-span artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack, galvanised and cast-iron rainwater goods and decorative polygonal clayware pots. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls over rubble stone masonry. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns, surrounding decorative metal radial fanlight with moulded ashlar archivolt above. Timber sliding sash tripartite windows to side elevation. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered retaining wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to entrance level. Stone flagged steps to basement area.

NAME: Dr. Patrick O'Donnell / The Well Spring Gallery
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1810, with two-storey split-level return and two-storey extensions to rear c. 1972. Now also in use as surgery, and having art gallery to basement. Pitched double-span purple slate roof with rendered chimneystack, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with projecting metal sign. Timber one-over-one sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with painted lintel surrounded by engaged Ionic columns having fanlight above with moulded archivolt. Top hung outward opening window and timber flush door to basement area. Wrought-iron railings on limestone plinth. Stone steps up to front. Concrete steps to basement area. Attached two-storey rubble stone outbuilding to rear with single-pitched artificial slate roof and rubble stone walls.

NAME: Ashe Townhouse B & B
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1810, with three-storey split-level return and various extensions to rear. Now in use as a guesthouse. Pitched double-span purple slate roof with rendered chimneystack, concrete barge to party wall and uPVC rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel surrounded by engaged Ionic columns having radial fanlight above with carved archivolt. Timber matchboard doors and horizontal bars to basement level. Wrought-iron railings on limestone plinth. Limestone steps up to front door. Slate flag steps down to basement. Attached two-storey rubble stone outbuilding to rear with single-pitched artificial slate roof and brick arches to openings to lane to rear. Vaulted coal house under pavement to front.

Attached six-bay three-storey over basement former bank, built 1928, with single-storey extension to rear c. 1980. Undergoing substantial renovation works 2003. Pitched hipped slated roof with brick chimneystack having moulded limestone cornice. Flat metallised felt roof to extension. Channelled limestone ashlar walls with engaged Ionic columns having entablature above to ground floor. Red brick walls with limestone string course at sill levels to upper levels, having limestone parapet wall with mutules. Timber one-over-one sliding sash windows with limestone sills and moulded limestone surrounds, pedimented to second floor. Timber panelled double leaf doors with toplights to either end of ground floor. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth. Limestone steps to front doors.

NAME: J. D. Wynne & Co.
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1820, with stair projection and two-storey return to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron gutter. Lined-and-ruled painted nap rendered walls. Timber one-over-one sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Timber panelled door with moulded lintel surrounded by engaged Ionic columns, having radial fanlight with moulded archivolt above. Timber panelled door with radial fanlight above, now covered with galvanised sheet to basement level. Wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth. Stone steps up to front door. Concrete steps down to basement.

NAME: Kerry Rape and Sexual Abuse Centre / Denis J. Reen
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1830, with two-storey pitched roofed extension and three-storey split-level return to rear, renovated in 1956. Now in use as offices and dental surgery. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Roughcast rendered walls to ground floor with raised render plinth and having inset marble surround to later ground floor window c. 1950. Nap rendered walls to upper floors. Timber sliding sash windows to upper floors. Timber top hug outward opening windows to ground floor. Double leaf timber panelled door with moulded lintel, surrounded by engaged Ionic columns with fanlight and moulded archivolt above. Stone steps up to front door. Two-storey former outbuilding to rear with rubble stone walls and pitched corrugated-iron roof, built 1914, now derelict.

Terraced five-bay three-storey former house with integral carriageway, built c. 1820, with stair return and single-storey extension to rear. Formerly in use as bank, later used as offices but currently vacant and undergoing refurbishment in 2003. Pitched purple slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack, polygonal clayware pots, cast-iron rainwater goods and having limestone blocking course over cornice to front elevation. Channelled rendered walls to ground floor. Lined-and-ruled painted nap rendered walls with quoins to upper floors, with string course at first floor sill level and having moulded dentilled string course below cornice. Timber sliding sash windows with decorative stucco surrounds and painted limestone sills. Timber panelled door with plain fanlight having stucco rope moulded archivolt surround above. Carved stone ancons to openings. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth with ashlar limestone piers. Ashlar step up to front door.

Terraced three-bay three-storey over inferred basement former house, built c. 1810, with single-storey extension to rear c. 1970. Recently in use as offices, but currently vacant. Pitched natural slate roof with rendered chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots, cast-iron rainwater goods and having limestone blocking course over projecting cornice with scrolls. Channelled rendered walls to ground floor. Lined-and-ruled painted nap rendered walls with quoins to upper floors, string course at sill level to first floor, and having moulded dentilled string course below cornice. Timber sliding sash windows surrounded by decorative raised render moulding, having painted limestone sills to ground and third floors. Timber panelled doors with fanlight surrounded by rope moulded archivolt with carved head keystone. Alternating key stones to side opening. Cast-iron railings on limestone plinth with limestone piers. Limestone step to front door.

NAME: Tralee Beauty Salon
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1810, three-storey pitched roofed extension to rear and two-storey flat roofed extension to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered lined-and-ruled walls. Timber sliding sash windows to ground and first floors with limestone sills. Timber top hung outward opening windows to top floor with limestone sills. Boarded openings to basement. Timber panelled door with carved stone lintel, surrounded by engaged Ionic columns and margin lights, having radial fanlight with moulded archivolt above. Cast-iron railings on rendered plinth. Stone steps up to front door and down to basement. North party wall of former outbuilding to rear remains with rubble stone and brick structure.

Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1820, with single-storey extension to rear. Formerly used as hotel, later used as offices, currently vacant. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods decorated with chevron pattern. Flat roof to extension. Ashlar limestone facing to ground floor walls. Nap rendered lined-and-ruled walls above string courses at sill levels on upper floors. Timber top hung outward opening windows to upper floors. Timber panelled door with toplight having pilaster and entablature surround. Moulded raised decorative surround to openings. Cast-iron railings on stone plinth.

NAME: AXA Insurance
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1820, with single-storey extension to rear. Later used as hotel, now in use as offices, renovated to ground floor in1999. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods decorated with chevron pattern, and having carved cornice and mutules to eaves course. Nap rendered walls with raised string courses at sill levels. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows to upper floors. Recent timber fixed window to ground floor, flanked by timber glazed door with toplight and timber panelled door with toplight and margin lights, surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront. Wrought-iron railing on painted rendered plinth. Limestone steps up to front door.

NAME: Health Centre
COMPOSITION: Terraced four-bay three-storey office, built 1964, with shopfront to ground floor. Pitched natural slate roof with rendered chimneystack and polygonal clayware pots. Cement panel facing to upper storeys with pilasters clad in mosaic tiles. Timber shopfront, inserted 1993, to ground floor. Aluminium horizontal pivot windows with raised cement surrounds to upper floors. Timber fixed windows with glazed door and panelled door having toplights surrounded by pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor.

NAME: John Joe Sheehy Finance
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1820, now in use as offices. Pitched natural slate roof with rendered chimneystack, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron gutter. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with render quoins. Timber painted shop sign to ground floor. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight. Timber fixed window to shopfront having glazed timber door with metal grille and painted timber shop sign above.

NAME: Ireland Designs
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey former house, built c. 1815, with two-storey extension to rear. Now in use as shop and offices with timber pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Single-pitched roof to extension. Nap rendered walls with moulded quoins. Timber pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor. Moulded circular panel between second and third storeys with painted metal fixture. uPVC top hung outward opening windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Timber fixed window to ground floor with panelled timber door and glazed door surrounded by timber pilaster and entablature shopfront, supported on limestone plinth.

NAME: Supermacs
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace former house, built 1826, formerly used as retail outlet, now in use as restaurant premises, refurbished 2003. Pitched and hipped mineralised felt over slate roof with cast-iron rooflight, rendered chimneystack, polygonal clayware pots and projecting cornice. Channelled rendered walls to ground floor. Nap rendered walls with moulded quoins to upper floors having moulded string courses at sill levels. Timber sliding sash windows with moulded stucco decorative surrounds to upper floors. Fixed timber round-arched windows and aluminium half glazed fixed windows to ground floor. Stucco pilaster and entablature shopfront to ground floor. West party wall reputed to be extant wall of former castle.

NAME: Mike Mc Carthy Hairstylist
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay four-storey house, built c. 1760, now with hairdressers to ground floor. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods, and having concrete barging to party wall.  Painted nap rendered walls over rubble stone structure.  Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills to upper floors. Fixed timber window with timber panelled doors having toplights to ground floor. Remnants of a timber shopfront.  Limestone carved gutter to rear yard.

End-of-terrace three-bay three-storey house, built c. 1795, with two-storey return to rear. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with wrought-iron lamp bracket. Rubble stone with inset brick to gable wall. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and fluted pilasters surround, having radial fanlight with moulded ashlar archivolt above. Boarded openings to basement.

NAME: Ozanam House
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1795, with single-storey over basement extension to rear c. 1985. Formerly Tralee Catholic Literary Society, now in use as offices. Pitched double-span artificial slate roof with box aluminium gutter and cast-iron down pipe. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Replacement timber side hung outward opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and fluted pilasters surround, having radial fanlight with decorative applied ornament above. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to door. Concrete steps down to basement area.

NAME: Liston Solicitors
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1795, with three-storey single-pitched roofed extension and conservatory to rear. Now also in use as offices. Pitched double-span artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Stucco label mouldings and under sill decoration on top two floors openings. Stucco architrave to ground floor openings. Top hung outward opening windows to top floor. uPVC windows to rear. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and fluted Ionic pilasters surround having radial fanlight above. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps and wrought-iron boot scrape to front door. Concrete steps to basement. Concrete block façade to rear with galvanised openings. Rubble stone outbuilding with some original slate.

NAME: Malone O' Regan Mc Gillicuddy
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1795, with three-storey return and single-storey conservatory to rear. Now in use as offices. Pitched double-span natural slate roof having cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins. Slate cladding to rear wall. Timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns surround, having radial timber fanlight above with moulded ashlar archivolt above. Boarded window and timber glazed door to basement. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to front door. Two-storey outbuilding to rear with pitched corrugated-iron roof, rubble stone walls and having sliding galvanised and timber matchboard doors. Stone steps to basement.

Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1795, in use as meeting rooms Fianna Fail Cumann since 1941, with apartment to top floor.  Pitched double-span natural slate roof with cast-iron gutter and nap rendered chimneystack. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with moulded render quoins. Aluminium top hung outward opening windows with stone sills. Blocked openings at basement level. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns surrounding, having radial timber fanlight with moulded ashlar archivolt above. Timber matchboard door to basement. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to front door. Two-storey outbuilding to rear with pitched corrugated-iron roof, rubble stone walls, blocked openings, and having rubble elliptical arch to former coach house.

NAME: Carmady Leen O' Donnell & Co.
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, rebuilt behind façade c. 1985. Now in use as offices with three-storey return to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Replacement uPVC top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns surrounding, having plain fanlight over with moulded ashlar archivolt. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to door. Concrete steps down to basement area. Wrought-iron boot scrape. Two-storey outbuilding to rear with flat roof and having nap and roughcast rendered walls.

Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, formerly with split-level two-storey return to rear, currently being radically renovated (2003). Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls with canted ashlar string course at ground  floor level. Replacement timber sliding sash windows in 2003, not to original pattern, with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns surrounding, having radial fanlight with moulded ashlar archivolt above. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to door having cast-iron boot scrape. Stone flag steps down to basement area. Rubble stone boundary walls to rear.

Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, with two-storey over basement split-level return. Now in use as museum since c. 1995 renovation. Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack, projecting ashlar eaves course, metal gutter brackets and cast-iron rainwater goods. Cement rendered walls with lined-and-ruled voussoirs to windows and having pre-cast concrete moulded quoins. Replacement timber sliding sash windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns surrounding, having new radial timber fanlight over with moulded ashlar archivolt. Timber half glazed panelled door with sidelights to basement. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to door having cast-iron boot scrape. Slated steps down to basement area. Rubble stone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Peter Moran
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1800, with two-storey over basement extension to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Lined-and-ruled nap rendered walls. Replacement uPVC top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with carved lintel and engaged Ionic columns surrounding, having plain fanlight over with moulded archivolt. Paired timber sliding sash windows c. 1950 in single opening, with shallow segmental-arched opening over to rear ground floor. Decorative wrought-iron railings on decorative plinth with stone coping. Stone steps up to door. Stone steps down to basement area. Two-storey outbuilding to rear with concrete block and rubble stone walls and pitched corrugated-sheet roof. Timber matchboard sliding door to lane to rear.

NAME: Law Centre
COMPOSITION: Corner-sited end-of-terrace three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built 1853, used as Roman Catholic chapel c. 1860-1870, now in use as offices, renovated c. 1995. Pitched double-span hipped artificial slate roof. Cement rendered walls with limestone quoins to frontage and roughcast rendered walls to sides. Replacement uPVC top hung outward opening windows with limestone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight, having timber fluted Ionic pilasters and entablature surround. Timber glazed double leaf doors to basement. Decorative wrought-iron railings on rendered plinth wall with stone coping. Stone steps up to door c. 1990. Rubble stone steps down to basement area.

Detached three-bay two-storey former barracks, built c. 1915, with pediment to central bay. Six-bay two-storey extension to left hand side, two-bay two-storey extension to right hand side. Hipped artificial slate roof with ashlar limestone chimneystacks, uPVC gutter, cast-iron downpipe and having limestone ashlar eaves courses to flanking bays. Channelled ashlar limestone walls and nap rendered walls. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills and carved limestone surrounds with keystones above. Round-arched opening to central bay. uPVC glazed sliding door. Concrete steps and ramp with cast metal railings up to entrance door. Nap rendered boundary walls. Single-storey outbuilding to site.

Semi-detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1915, central bays are projecting and gabled. Single-storey extension to rear. Now in use as post office. Pitched natural slate roof with red brick chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gabled bay and having hipped single-pitched artificial slate roof to bay window. Nap rendered walls with red brick quoins to gabled bay and having sandstone quoins to left hand sides. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills and red brick surrounds. Bay window to right hand side ground floor. Timber panelled door with toplight and red brick surrounds. Rubble stone boundary walls to rear. Nap rendered boundary walls with red brick piers to front.

Semi-detached two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1915, with single-storey extension to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with render quoins. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills and red brick surrounds. Timber panelled door with toplight and red brick surround. Nap rendered boundary walls. Rubble stone boundary walls to rear. Single-storey outbuilding.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey officers quarters, built c. 1810, with three-bay two-storey extension to rear. Hipped natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron rainwater goods. Ashlar limestone chimneystacks to extension. Roughcast rendered walls, with brick arched recess to extension and having limestone string courses at impost level. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight and ashlar limestone surround. Rubble stone boundary walls with limestone ashlar surrounds to openings and limestone piers with cast metal double leaf gates.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey prison, built c. 1810, now in poor condition. Pitched natural slate roof with concrete barging to party walls, red brick chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods and having limestone ashlar at eaves course. Nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with cast-iron grilles and stone sills. Timber panelled door with ashlar limestone surround. Segmental-arched openings with cast-iron grilles. Loop openings with ashlar limestone surrounds.  Roger Casement reputedly held here.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Detached six-bay two-storey over basement officer's quarters, built c. 1810, with extension to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods and having timber bargeboards to gables. Flat roof to extension. Nap rendered walls. uPVC top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight and ashlar limestone surround. Red brick wall of former building to rear.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey former hospital, built c. 1810, with single- and two-storey projections to front façade and having two-storey extension to rear. Now in use as dormitories. Pitched natural slate roof with ashlar limestone and nap rendered chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods, hipped natural slate roof to two-storey projections, single-pitched roof to single-storey projection and having ashlar limestone eaves course. Nap rendered walls. Broken render to rear shows limestone quoins and snecked ashlar sandstone. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight and ashlar limestone surround. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows to rear extension. Concrete steps up to rear front door.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Attached two-bay two-storey former doctor's house, built c. 1840, attached to former military hospital. Hipped natural slate roof with red brick chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Red brick walls. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills set in segmental-arched opening. Matchboard door to rear. Rubble limestone boundary wall to rear.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Attached eight-bay single-storey former barrack, built c. 1850, with three-bay single-storey extension to gable. Now in use as public house. Pitched natural slate roof with red brick chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber flush door with toplight and canopy above.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Attached seven-bay single-storey dining hall, built c. 1850. Pitched double-span natural slate roof with rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Roughcast rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Timber matchboard door.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Attached fifteen-bay two-storey barracks with adjoining single-bay two-storey block to left hand side, built c. 1810. Pitched natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber matchboard doors with toplights and ashlar limestone surrounds. Existing structure is half of original soldiers quarters, other half of structure destroyed in 1921.

NAME: Military Barracks
COMPOSITION: Detached gable-fronted three-bay single-storey former store, built c. 1900, now disused. Pitched natural slate roof with red brick chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron metal. Red brick walls. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber flush doors with toplight.

NAME: Castlemorris House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay three-storey over basement house, built c. 1830, with single- and two-storey extensions to rear. Formerly residence of army officer in neighbouring barracks. Hipped natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron rainwater goods. Single-pitched artificial slate roof to extensions. Nap rendered walls with render quoins. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills. Timber matchboard double leaf doors formerly surrounded by glazed timber porch with half glazed door. Bay windows to left hand side gable wall. Limestone steps up to front door. Roughcast rendered boundary walls with wrought-iron railings. Single-storey outbuildings to rear.

NAME: Cloghers Gatelodge
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay single-storey former gate lodge, built c. 1880, with projecting porch and single-bay single-storey extension to right hand side. Now in use as private house. Pitched natural slate roof with timber bargeboards, modillions, nap rendered chimneystacks, polygonal clayware pots and cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls. Timber windows with stone and concrete sills. Timber matchboard door with half door and cast metal bell. Semi-circular arched opening to rear. Nap rendered boundary walls with render panels and wrought-iron double leaf gates.

Detached five-bay two-storey over basement house with projecting central bay, built c. 1880, with glazed timber porch, and having single-bay three-storey over basement extension to rear. Hipped natural slate roof with timber modillions to oversailings eaves, ashlar limestone chimneystacks and cast-iron rainwater goods. Roughcast rendered walls. Timber sliding sash windows with moulded stone sills having pilaster and entablature surrounds. Timber half glazed door with toplight and sidelights having carved timber detailing above. Fixed timber lancet windows set in segmental-arched openings with render surrounds to east. Limestone steps to front door.

NAME: Castlemorris
COMPOSITION: Remains of Castle-Morris c. 1450, with later attached rubble stone walls c. 1840, forming boundary to Ballymullen Road.

NAME: Castledesmond House
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1840, with single-bay single-storey extension to right hand side. Flat roof with render bands at eaves course, cast-iron rainwater goods, and having pitched natural slate roof to extension. Nap rendered walls with render quoins. Timber sliding sash windows with stone sills and render surround. Timber panelled door with sidelights and fanlight having render surround. Fixed timber window to round-arched opening to rear. Timber top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows to extension. Nap rendered plinth with wrought-iron railings and gate. Limestone steps and cast-metal railings up to back door.

Detached eight-bay three-storey former warehouse, built c. 1870, now vacant. Pitched natural slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with cement rendered wall to rear gable and having metal bracing. Timber matchboard boarding to openings. Timber matchboard doors. Concrete boundary wall to rear.

Detached three-bay three-storey over basement former house, built c. 1835. Hipped artificial slate roof with cast-iron rainwater goods and nap rendered chimneystack. Cement rendered walls. Single and tripartite timber sliding sash windows with painted stone sills. Timber half glazed door with side and fanlight. Dressed stone boundary walls with timber double leaf gates. Limestone steps to front door with wrought-iron railings.

NAME: Hanlon's
COMPOSITION: Semi-detached three-bay two-storey house, built 1904, with vacant retail outlet to ground floor. Single and two-storey extensions to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with cement rendered chimneystacks and uPVC rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with render quoins and painted timber shop sign. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills and render surrounds. Timber panelled door with toplight and render surround. Timber fixed window and timber half glazed door with sidelights and toplight, having render surrounds and cornice above.

NAME: Sisters of Mercy Convent
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay two-storey convent, built 1888, with integral chapel, two terminating bays are gabled. Five-bay two-storey extension to rear adjoining nine-bay two-storey extension also to rear. Various single-storey extensions to sides and rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack and uPVC rainwater goods. Pitched natural slate roof with crested ridge tiles to nine-bay extension. Flat roof to extension. Bellcote to nine-bay extension and mutules at eaves level. Nap rendered walls with limestone plinth and quoins and having aedicules with statues. Timber sliding sash windows set in pointed segmental-arched openings with limestone sills, limestone surrounds and having label mouldings to some openings. Timber and metal lancet stained glass windows. Timber top-hug outward-opening windows with concrete sills. Timber panelled front door with sidelights and toplight. Timber panelled and glazed doors.

End-of-terrace two-bay two-storey with attic accommodation house, built c. 1910, with two-storey extension to rear. Hipped natural slate roof with rooflight, hipped single-pitched roof to ground floor bays, crested ridge tiles, red brick chimneystack, and uPVC rainwater goods. Red brick walls with painted stone string courses. Snecked ashlar limestone to extension. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with moulded stone sills. Timber half glazed door with toplight. Bay window to ground floor. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, left hand side bay is gabled. Two-storey extension to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with dormer window, crested ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gabled bay, and having single-pitched artificial slate porch roof. Red brick walls with limestone string courses. Timber top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with moulded stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, right hand side bay is gabled. Two-storey extension to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with dormer window, crested ridge tiles, single-pitched artificial slate porch roof, timber bargeboards to gabled bay, and cast-iron rainwater goods. Red brick walls with painted limestone string courses. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills. Timber panelled door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, with two-storey extension to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with dormer window, crested ridge tiles, hipped single-pitched slate to porch roof and having cast-iron rainwater goods. Red brick walls with painted limestone string courses. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills. Bay window to ground floor. Half glazed door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls with piers and cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, with two-storey extension to rear. Now also in use as guest house. Pitched artificial slate roof with dormer window, crested ridge tiles, red brick chimneystack, uPVC rainwater goods and having hipped single-pitched artificial slate to porch roof. Red brick walls with painted limestone string courses. uPVC top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills. Bay window to ground floor. uPVC panelled door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls with piers and cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, left hand side bay is gabled. Two-storey extension to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with dormer window, crested ridge tiles, cast-iron rainwater goods, single-pitched natural slate to porch roof, and having timber bargeboards to gabled bay. Red brick walls with limestone string courses. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Timber glazed double leaf doors with side and toplights. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, right hand side bay is gabled. Two-storey extension to rear. Pitched natural slate roof with dormer window, crested ridge tiles, red brick chimneystack, cast-iron rainwater goods, single-pitched natural slate to porch roof, and having timber bargeboards to gabled bay. Red brick walls and limestone string courses. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills. Timber half glazed double leaf doors with side and toplights. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

End-of-terrace two-bay two-storey house with attic accommodation, built c. 1910, with single- and two-storey extension to rear. Hipped natural slate roof with rooflights, crested ridge tiles, uPVC rainwater goods, and having hipped single-pitched natural slate porch roof. Red brick walls and limestone string courses. uPVC top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills. Bay window to ground floor. uPVC half glazed door with toplight. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows to gable wall. Red brick boundary walls with piers and cast-iron railings and gate.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1915, right hand side bay has bay windows and gablet. Two-storey extension to rear with adjoining single-storey extension. Hipped natural slate roof with crested ridge tiles, red brick chimneystacks, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gablet and having flat roof to bay window. Nap rendered walls with string course at sill level first floor. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows, with render surrounds to first floor left hand side opening. Timber panelled door with sidelights, fanlight and render surround. Red brick boundary walls and piers, having cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1915, left hand side bay has bay windows with gablet. Two-storey extension to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with crested ridge tiles, rooflights, cast-iron rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gablet, and having flat roof to bay window. Nap rendered walls with moulded string courses. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills. Render surrounds to right hand side first floor opening. Timber panelled door with sidelights, fanlight and render surround. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

NAME: Brook House
COMPOSITION: Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1915, right hand side bay has bay windows and gablet. Two-storey extension to rear. Pitched artificial slate roof with red brick chimneystack, uPVC rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gablet and having flat roof to bay window. Nap rendered walls with moulded string courses. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows. Render surround to left hand side first floor opening. Timber panelled door with sidelights, fanlights and render surround. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1915, left hand side bay has bay windows and gablet. Two-storey extension. Pitched artificial slate roof with uPVC rainwater goods, timber bargeboards to gablet and having flat roof to bay window. Nap rendered walls with moulded string courses. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows. Render surround to right hand side first floor opening, Timber panelled door with sidelights, fanlights and render surround. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings gate.

End-of-terrace two-bay three-storey house, built c. 1915, right hand side bay has bay windows and gablet. Two-storey extension to rear. Hipped artificial slate roof with cement rendered chimneystack and uPVC rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with moulded string course. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows. Render surround to left hand side first floor opening. Timber half glazed double leaf doors with fanlight. Red brick boundary walls and piers with cast-iron railings and gate.

NAME: Clonmore House Gate Lodge
COMPOSITION:
Detached three-bay single-storey former gate lodge, built c. 1855, central bay is projecting. Now in use as private house. Hipped natural slate roof with nap rendered chimneystack, polygonal clayware pot and cast-iron rainwater goods. Ashlar limestone and sandstone walls. uPVC top-hung outward-opening windows with painted stone sills. uPVC panelled door. Ashlar limestone boundary walls.
Mian house, Clonmore House, is now demolished

NAME: Gaelcholaiste Chiarrai
COMPOSITION: Detached seven-bay single-storey former library with seven-bay two-storey extension to rear and three-bay two-storey recessed flanking extensions, built c. 1915. Now in use as school having two- and three-bay two-storey extensions to left hand side, various single- and two-storey extensions to sides and rear. Flat roof with moulded cornices and limestone parapet, nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Nap rendered walls with render quoins. Timber sliding sash and top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with stone sills and render surrounds. Timber panelled double leaf door with fanlight and render archivolt flanked by limestone Doric columns. Timber panelled double leaf doors with toplights. Nap rendered boundary walls and piers.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1905. Pitched natural slate roof with sandstone mutules, uPVC rainwater goods and nap rendered chimneystack. Red brick walls with sandstone string course. uPVC side-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Timber half glazed door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1905. Pitched artificial slate roof with uPVC rainwater goods and sandstone mutules. Red brick walls with sandstone string course. Timber side-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Timber flush door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls with cast-iron railings and gate.

Terraced two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1905. Pitched natural slate roof with sandstone mutules, nap rendered chimneystack and cast-iron rainwater goods. Red brick walls with sandstone string course. uPVC top-hung outward-opening and side-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. uPVC panelled door with toplight. Red brick boundary walls with cast-iron railings and gate.

End-of-terrace two-bay two-storey house, built c. 1905, with single-bay single-storey extension to right hand side. Hipped artificial slate roof with sandstone eaves course, cast-iron rainwater goods and having flat roof to extension. Red brick walls with sandstone string course. Timber top-hung outward-opening windows with limestone sills. Aluminium glazed door with toplight and timber panelled door. Red brick boundary walls with cast-iron railings and gate.

NAME: Saint Michael The Archangel's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding seven-bay single- and double-height Hiberno Romanesque style Roman Catholic church, begun 1871, designed by J.J. Mc Carthy.  Comprising seven-bay double-height nave with six-bay single-storey lean-to aisles to north and to south elevations, single-bay two-stage truncated tower to north-west, rose window to east gable end, three-bay single-storey chapel to south-west and single-bay full-height bowed apse to west gable end.  Interior re-ordered c. 1975.  Extended to north, c. 1980, with two-bay single-storey flat-roofed sacristy.  Pitched slate roofs to nave and sacristy with lean-to slate roofs to aisles, clay ridge tiles and having cast-iron rainwater goods on limestone corbels.  Curved copper clad roof to apse.  Replacement artificial slate pyramidal roof to tower, with louvered timber lantern having copper-clad dome and iron crucifix finial.  Snecked squared rubble stone walls, with rock-hewn ashlar buttresses and quoins. Imitation ashlar block work to sacristy.  Paired round-headed window openings to aisles and to clerestory and single openings to east and to west walls, having dressed cut-limestone surrounds.  Fixed-pane windows, round-headed door openings and ledged and braced timber double leaf doors with strap hinges.  Limestone steps to entrances.  Full-height interior open into roof.  Tiled floor.  Replacement glazed timber lobby, c. 1950.  Round-headed arcade to side aisles with pink marble and stone columns having foliate capitals and moulded red brick archivolts.  Gallery to first floor to west.  Stained glass window to west.  Clear glass windows to side aisles and to clerestory.  Open scissors truss timber roof.  Chancel arch on paired pilasters.  Tiled floor to altar.  White marble font.  Stained glass windows to altar and to side altars.  Ribbed ceiling to apse.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers, c. 1875-present.  Detached presbytery, c. 1965, to site.  Detached school, c. 1980, to site.

Detached four-bay two-storey former mill, built c. 1850, now in use as store.  Pitched and hipped slate roof with cast-iron rooflights to east and clay ridge tiles.  Painted random rubble stone walls.  Square-headed openings with timber lintels, no sills, timber casement windows and shutters.  Timber door to ground floor opening onto Ballyline River.  Timber door to first floor opening onto street.  Street fronted on site adjacent to Ballylongford Bridge.  Tarmacadam road to south.  River fronted to west.

Detached single-bay five-storey gable-fronted mill, built c. 1860, with twelve bay side elevations and having cantilevered hoist-canopy to gable.  Now disused.  Single-bay single-storey lean-to end bay to north.  Attached three-bay two-storey barrel-roofed block, built c. 1940, to north with three-bay single-storey lean-to projecting bay to east and corrugated-iron roof.  Pitched slate roof with clay ridge tiles and metal flue to north.  Snecked limestone ashlar walls with hammered limestone quoins to front gable.  Random rubble stone walls to side elevations.  Unpainted roughcast rendered walls west gable.  Square-headed openings with hammered limestone sills, lintels and voussoirs and multiple pane timber casement windows to front façade.  Red brick block-and-start surrounds to side elevations with four-pane timber casement windows.  Square-headed door openings to ground floor and to gable to east.  Timber panelled double doors.  Gabled timber canopy to door (loading) opening to gable on limestone corbels.  Detached five-bay two-storey building, built c. 1940, to north-east.  Set back from street in own grounds.

NAME: M. Finnucane
COMPOSITION: Terraced three-bay two-storey house, built c. 1880, now also in use as public house.  Pitched artificial slate roof with concrete ridge tiles, box eaves and cast-iron rainwater goods including decorative 'barley-sugar' style downpipe.  Painted nap rendered walls.  Rendered shopfront with pilasters, decorative consoles, raised lettering and dentilated cornice surrounding fixed windows and timber panelled double doors with over panel.  Square-headed openings with stone sills, moulded rendered architraves to first floor and timber casement windows.  Street fronted with concrete footpath to front.

NAME: Kilelton Farm Yard
COMPOSITION: Farmyard complex, built c. 1860, originally about a courtyard, comprising farmhouse and related farm buildings.  Detached four-bay two-storey house, with pitched slate roof, concrete ridge tiles, nap rendered chimneystack, plastic ports, concrete coping to gable ends, timber eaves and plastic rainwater goods.  Painted nap rendered walls.  Square-headed openings with stone sills and replacement timber casement windows. Replacement glazed timber panelled door.  Detached ten-bay single-storey rubble stone-built range to south-east on an L-shaped plan with single-bay single-storey flat-roofed projecting bay to south-east.  Pitched and hipped slate roofs, with sections of corrugated-iron, having concrete ridge tiles and cast-iron rainwater goods.  Painted or lime washed random rubble stone walls.  Pair of blind lunette window openings to north-east.  Square-headed door openings with stone lintels and timber doors.  Detached five-bay double-height corrugated-iron barrel-roofed barn building, built c. 1980, to south-west with five-bay single-storey lean-to projecting bay to front and corrugated-iron roof.  Open arcade with iron pillars.  Set back from road in own grounds.  Gateway to east comprising pair of rendered panelled piers with finials.  Landscaped grounds to site with avenue to farm yard complex.

NAME: O'Coileain
COMPOSITION: Detached four-bay two-storey house, built c. 1860, renovated and extended with single-bay single-storey return to rear, built c. 1920, and shopfront inserted to ground floor.  Later used as shop, now vacant.  Pitched slate roof with clay ridge tiles, rendered chimneystacks and cast-iron gutters.  Pyramidal roof to return.  Ruled-and-lined painted rendered walls with raised render quoins and consoles to eaves.  Render shopfront with fascia signboard with lettering, moulded cornice, scroll brackets and pilasters.  one-over-one pane timber sliding sash windows with moulded render architraves and painted sills.  Timber four-panel doors with plinth blocks and overlight.  Rendered boundary walls and gate posts to site.  Three-bay two-storey coach-house to south with rubble walls and slate roof to site.

NAME: Saint Mary's Presbytery
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey Jacobean Revival style presbytery, dated 1878, on a square plan with gabled doorcase to entrance bay to centre having gablet over, single-bay full-height gabled advanced end bay to right and three-bay side elevations having canted bay window to west elevation.  Reroofed and refenestrated, 1991.  Pitched artificial slate roofs having ashlar chimneystack with cornices and replacement rainwater goods.  Sections of original profiled iron gutters remain.  Rock-hewn snecked limestone with hammered quoins and plinth course, moulded strings to gables and having carved springers.  uPVC windows with hammered limestone lintels, tooled sills and reveals.  Hammered limestone single-storey bay window.  Projecting ashlar gabled doorcase with uPVC door and trefoil overlight.  Rubble stone relieving arches.  Detached two-bay single-storey outbuilding, built c. 1880, to north-east.  Gateway, built c. 1880, to north-west comprising pair of cut-limestone piers with triangular capping.  Carved limestone free-standing plaque in front of presbytery mounted on former ridge-stone.  Plaque read 'This presbytery built by James Quin Tarvert in 1878 to house the first Parish Priest of the new parish of Tarbert (1859) renovated 1991 and dedicated to Father Dan Foley and his successors".

NAME: Saint Mary's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1833, comprising seven-bay nave, single-bay single-storey gabled advanced confessionals to north-west and to south-west elevations, belfry to south-west, single-bay full-height transepts to north-east and to south-east and single-bay full-height chancel to east gable end.  Later single-bay single-storey gabled projecting porches added to west gable end and west elevations of transepts.  Single-bay single-storey flat-roofed sacristy projection added to east gable end.  Pitched slate roof with projecting concrete eaves and verges.  Pebbledashed walls with render plinth and margins.  Lancet arch openings to nave and triple lancets to transepts and over west gable entrance.  Concrete sills to openings with render surrounds.  Projecting gabled porches with timber doors.  T-plan interior with a shallow chancel recess.  Exposed scissor truss roof with exposed rafters and purloins.  Rendered dado with beaded rail.  Panelled dado to chancel including pointed arch to reredos.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers, c. 1835-present.

NAME: Corpus Christi Catholic Church
COMPOSITION:
Freestanding double-height flat-roofed International Modern style single-cell Roman Catholic church, dated 1963, with four-bay side elevations.  Concrete slab roof with beams.  Buff-coloured concrete brick side walls in English bond.  Metal framed glazed screen walls with similar framed clerestory windows between beams of roof.  Single volume interior with carved screen forming porch, plastered screen as reredos and half-height timber partitions to sacristy and offices.  Concrete flagged floor and concrete brick walls.  Polished limestone altar, lectern and font.  Freestanding iron belfry, built c. 1965, to south-east of site possibly incorporating bell of earlier church.  Concrete flagged podium and steps to front at same level as internal floor.
Architect Ronald Tallon - Michael Scott & Partners.

NAME: Ballyheigue Castle
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached two- and three-storey Tudor Gothic Revival style country house, built 1809, incorporating fabric of earlier house, 1758.  Comprising six-bay two-storey side (south) elevation of entrance block with battlemented parapet, single-bay three-storey battlemented corner turrets on circular plans and nine-bay two-storey lower wing (originally return) to west having battlemented parapet and corner machicolation.  Burnt, in 1840, later used as prison, burnt, in 1921 and now mostly collapsed.  Wing reconstructed and remodelled, c. 1975, to accommodate use as apartments with remainder of building now ruinous.  Castellated parapets with one cast-iron hopper having floral motif.  Snecked sandstone walls with grey limestone string courses and plinth, castellated machicolations, blind arrow loops and having render to parts of side wall with imitation ashlar.  Square-headed openings with limestone sills, surrounds, hood mouldings and having sandstone relieving arches.  Timber window frames in side openings.  Four-centred arch to doorway in double-height arch having window above with carved spandrels.  Detached nine-bay two-storey Tudor Gothic Revival style former stable complex, built c. 1810, to east on an L-shaped plan about a courtyard with battlemented parapet, with single-bay two-storey corner turret on a circular plan and three-bay side elevations.  Extensively renovated in latter part of twentieth century with pair of single-bay single-storey gabled projecting porches added to accommodate use as apartments.  Detached six-bay single-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1810, to east on an L-shaped plan with series of elliptical-headed integral carriage arches, now disused.  Section of rubble stone boundary wall to east with series of arrow loops possibly originally part of walled garden.

NAME: Ballyheige Castle
COMPOSITION: Gateway to Ballyheige Castle, built c. 1830, comprising pair of single-bay two-storey lodge towers with cross apertures and battlemented parapets having elliptical-headed carriage arch to centre and single-bay single-storey flat-roofed end bay to south with battlemented parapet.  Lodge to north now disused.  Castellated parapet walls with sandstone copings.  Sandstone ashlar facing to front and rear facades with rubble stone side walls and blind arrow loops.  Pointed sandstone arches with limestone profiled sills and replacement windows.  Three-centred recessed carriage arch.

NAME: Saint Mary's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan single- and double-height Roman Catholic church, built 1837.  Comprising three-bay double-height nave with lancet arch openings, three-bay single-storey lean-to aisles to east and to west elevations, single-bay double-height transepts to east and to west elevations and single-bay double-height chancel to north gable end.  Renovated, 1910, with single-bay three-stage sandstone ashlar entrance tower added to south gable end having battlemented parapet and limestone ashlar hexagonal spire.  Nave reroofed and renovated in 1926.  Renovated in 1962 with pair of single-bay single-storey flat-roofed chapels added to south-east and to south-west.  Pitched artificial slate to nave, with lean-to copper-sheeted roofs to aisles, flat roofs to chapels and having limestone ashlar hexagonal spire.  Painted rendered walls.  Sandstone ashlar tower with limestone dressings.  Three plaques in wall.  Paired lancets to aisles with painted surrounds.  Render hood mouldings to west wall and transepts.  Cruciform-plan interior with aisles, pointed arcades on painted clustered columns, recessed west gallery, open trussed roof to nave and chancel, and stained glass panels c. 1925 to chancel and transepts.

NAME: Crotta House
COMPOSITION: Detached two-bay single-storey gate lodge with dormer attic, built c. 1850, originally with lancet arch openings to north gable end.  Openings later remodelled.  Now in use as private house.  Pitched slate roof with added cement gable parapets.  Random rubble stone walls with fragments of render.  Pointed arch blocked openings in north gable and one in south gable.  Red brick surrounded to first floor window.  Later openings formed in west wall.  Remains of rubble stone-built walls, built c. 1850, to south-west possibly originally part of walled garden.  Crotto House demolished in latter part of twentieth century.

NAME: Lixnaw Bridge
COMPOSITION: Double-arch road bridge over river, built c. 1725, with rubble stone voussoirs and parapet walls.  Renovated, c. 1950, with arch to west reconstructed.  Rubble stone parapet walls with concrete coping.  Swept arched openings, east arch with rubble stone voussoirs.

NAME: Old Court
COMPOSITION: Remains of detached five-bay two-storey country house, built c. 1680, extended, c. 1700, derelict in 1775.  Now ruinous.  Roughly coursed and squared rubble stone walls.  Walls step in and out on both faces of building.  Render fragments.  Timber lintels with stone relieving arches to openings.  Tall narrow window openings to west and north walls, sills removed.  Large fireplace to east wall interior with oven to left.  Ends of rubble partition walls to interior.  North end used as sheds at one time with evidence of lean-to roofs visible.  Short straight avenue of trees from road to north.

NAME: Saint Michael's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding ten-bay single- and double-height Romanesque style Roman Catholic church, dated 1865, designed by J.J. McCarthy.  Comprising ten-bay double-height nave with ten-bay single-storey lean-to aisles to north and to south elevations, single-bay single-storey sacristy to south elevation, rose window over entrance bay to west gable end and single-bay single-stage engaged circular turret to south-west corner on a square base having needle spire.  Renovated and extended to south-west in 1963 with single-bay single-storey limestone-built chapel.  Pitched artificial slate roofs, with gable parapets to sacristy, and cast-iron gutters and downpipes.  Rock-faced random limestone walls with smooth limestone dressings.  Corbel table to base of circular tower having ashlar conical roof.  Round-headed openings, limestone surrounds to clerestory windows and to west rose window, replacement concrete surrounds to aisle windows with exposed aggregate.  Door surround with columns, carving of St Michael in tympanum and double-leaf boarded doors.  Nave and two aisles separated by round-headed arcades to interior with limestone archivolts on limestone columns with foliate capitals.  Exposed trusses and compartmented ceilings.  Mosaic tiling to chancel walls at low level.  West gallery.  Chancel reordered.  Burial ground to site with group of cut-stone Celtic Cross style grave markers, c. 1900.  Gateway, built c. 1865, to west comprising four limestone ashlar circular piers with cast-iron gates and railings.  Lych gate, built c. 1865, to west comprising limestone ashlar piers with round-headed opening to centre having gable over with Celtic Cross style finial to apex.  Four circular limestone ashlar gateposts flanked by curved rubble walls with cast-iron gates and railings, partly replaced in steel.

NAME: Kerry Monument
COMPOSITION: Site of freestanding granite monument, built c. 1690, monument removed with single shaft remaining.

Corner-sited detached four-bay single-storey thatched house, built c. 1875, with single-bay single-storey return to rear to north.  Pitched and hipped thatched roof with rendered chimneystack.  Thatched renewed to front but in very poor condition at rear.  Painted rubble stone walls.  Timber two-over-two panes sliding sash windows with painted stone sills.  Timber half-door.  Set at north-west corner of crossroads in Finuge village.

NAME: Billeragh House
COMPOSITION: Detached five-bay two-storey mid-Georgian house, built c. 1780, retaining early fenestration to ground floor.  Renovated and refenestrated to first floor, to accommodate use as hostel.  Pitched and hipped slate roof with rendered chimneystack, clay ridge tiles and replacement gutters.  Roughcast rendered walls.  Timber one-over-one pane sliding sash windows to ground floor of façade, elsewhere uPVC windows, all with limestone sills.  Square-headed doorway with panelled timber door having overlight and stone threshold.  Timber panelled shutters to interior.  Detached four-bay two-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1800, to south-east with single-bay single-storey flanking end bays.  Detached single-bay single-storey gable-fronted rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1800, to north-west with two-bay side elevations, now ruinous.  Detached two-bay single-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1840, to north-east.  Curved avenue planted with mature beech trees.

NAME: Saint Bridget's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding six-bay single- and double-height Roman Catholic church, built c. 1870.  Comprising five-bay double-height nave with five-bay single-storey lean-to side aisles to north-east and to south-west elevations, single-bay single-storey gabled projecting porch to south-west elevation and single-bay double-height lower chancel to south-east gable end.  Pitched slate roofs to nave and chancel, lean-to aisles, with clay ridge tiles, gable parapets with limestone copings, crucifix finials and cast-iron gutters on metal brackets.  Sandstone rubble walls with limestone ashlar quoins and springers.  Lancets openings with limestone sills and surrounds, quatrefoil clerestory windows to south, lancet clerestory windows to north, bipartite west window and tripartite chancel window with trefoil heads to lancets.  West door converted to window.  Nave and two aisles separated by pointed arch arcades on limestone columns to interior.  Exposed trussed roof.  Fine triple-light stained glass window to chancel c. 1935.  Chancel remodelled with replacement white marble furnishings.  Finely carved font on marble.  Detached single-bay two-storey gable-fronted rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1870, to north with round-headed integral carriage arch to ground floor and five-bay side elevations.  Gateway, built c. 1870, to south-west comprising pair of render piers with decorative wrought-iron gates and railings.

NAME: Saint Bridget's Presbytery
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay two-storey presbytery, built c. 1915, with entrance bay to centre having gablet and two-storey flanking canted bay windows with pointed-arch openings to ground floor.  Two-bay side elevations to north-east and to south-west and single-bay two-storey lower return to rear to south-east.  Pitched and hipped slate roof with central valley, red brick chimneystack, clay ridge tiles, lead ridge rolls to bays and having gutter on brackets.  Painted rendered walls with recessed render panels to facade between ground and first floor, render strings at sill levels and eaves consoles.   Replacement uPVC windows set in pointed arch openings to ground floor and square-headed openings to first floor.  Paired pointed arch openings over pointed arch door opening with replacement uPVC door.  Set in the grounds of St Bridget's Church.

NAME: Saint Brendan's Catholic Church and Presbytery
COMPOSITION: Freestanding six-bay single- and double-height early-English Gothic Revival style Roman Catholic church, dated 1855, designed by J.J. McCarthy.  Comprising five-bay double-height nave with six-bay single-storey lean-to aisles to north and to south elevations, single-bay single-storey gabled projecting porch to south elevation, single-bay three-stage tower to south-west corner on a square plan having hexagonal broach spire, single-bay double-height lower chancel to east gable end with two-bay single-storey lean-to sacristy to south-east corner.  Renovated internally, c. 1885.  Pitched slate roof to nave with clay ridge comb, lean-to slate roofs to aisle, gable parapets with ashlar copings and carved springers and having ashlar hexagonal broach spire.  Snecked limestone walls, with buttresses to aisle walls, cruciform iron tie plates to clerestory and having profiled battered base to tower.  Trefoil-headed lancets to south wall, paired to aisle, single to clerestory.  Single lancets to north aisle and quatrefoils to clerestory.  Triple lancet chancel window.  Tracery to west windows.  Projecting gabled south porch with hood mouldings to doorways.  Open scissor-truss roof to nave interior with iron ties.  Lean-to aisles with pointed arched arcades on painted limestone columns.  Plaster stripped from walls and rubble pointed with cement.  Chancel reordered retaining carved stone reredos.  Graveyard to site with various cut-stone grave markers and mausolea, c. 1860-present.  Gateway, built c. 1885, to south comprising four limestone ashlar early-English Gothic Revival style piers with wrought-iron gates having Celtic Cross style finials.  Detached five-bay two-storey presbytery, built c. 1880, to south-west retaining original aspect with door opening to centre having moulded architrave and hood mouldings to window openings.  Attached three-bay two-storey rubble stone-built outbuilding, built c. 1880, at right angles to north-west on a T-shaped plan with four-bay single-storey wing to north-east.

NAME: Glandore Gates
COMPOSITION: Gateway, built c. 1815, by John Crosbie Earl of Glandore.  Comprising pair of limestone ashlar piers with lancet arch to centre having battlemented parapet over, cast-iron gates and curved screen wall to north.  Attached two-bay single-storey flat-roofed Gothic Revival style gate lodge, built c. 1815, to south, comprising single-bay linking bay with lancet arch openings and single-bay advanced end block having battlemented parapet and curved screen wall to south.  Relocated and reconstructed at present site, 1880.  Snecked limestone ashlar walls with hammered finish, battered buttresses to centre, carved crest with arrow loop over and having carved limestone plaque c. 1880 in archway.  Pointed archway with smooth limestone reveals.  Paired and triple lancet windows to lodge with timber lattice glazing bars.  Iron repousse double-leaf gates with crest.

NAME: Talbot-Crosbie Memorial
COMPOSITION: Freestanding Hiberno Romanesque style memorial fountain, dated 1901.  Comprising limestone ashlar plinth on a square-plan with shaft, having Romanesque sawtooth carving to red sandstone arches on corner pillars, having inscribed cast-iron plaque and pyramidal capping with corbelled eaves.  Bronze plaque inscribed: "1901 The Ardfert Water Supply was provided by Lieut Colonel Talbot-Crosbie and this fountain erected to his memory and for the public good by his brother Lindsay Talbot-Crosbie of Ardfert Abbey".

NAME: Ardfert Parish Room
COMPOSITION: Detached three-bay single-storey meeting hall with dormer attic, built c. 1915, with single-bay single-storey crow-stepped gabled projecting porch to left, crow-stepped gable ends and single-bay single-storey recessed end bay to east.  Built by local landlord Lindsey Talbot.  Now disused.  Pitched slate roofs with red clay ridge tiles (missing from main roof), limestone crow-step to gables, and having red brick chimneystack with stone cornice.  Red brick English garden bond walls with projecting plinth.  Pedimented limestone name plaque to west gable.  Timber multiple pane casement windows with limestone sills, lintels and mullions and having chamfered brick reveals.  Projecting gabled porch having round-headed doorway with brick arch.  Square-headed doorway to east end with limestone lintel.  Gateway, built c. 1915, to south comprising pair of red brick piers with limestone ashlar capping having wrought-iron gates and railings.  Stone boundary walls with rounded copings.

NAME: Catholic Church of the Sacred Heart
COMPOSITION: Freestanding six-bay single- and double-height Gothic Revival Roman Catholic church, dated 1873.  Comprising six-bay double-height nave, single-bay single-storey lean-to projecting porch to north-west, six-bay single-storey lean-to aisle to south elevation, single-bay full-height polygonal apse to west gable end and bellcote over east gable.  Pitched slate roof to nave, lean-to slate roofs to aisle and porch, with clay ridge tiles, ashlar pilastered bellcote to west gable, ashlar chimneystack to sacristy, and having profiled gutter on corbels.  Snecked rock-hewn limestone walls with hammered quoins, smooth plinth and sill courses.  Stepped buttresses to north nave wall.  Paired lancets with hexafoils over, all having smooth limestone surrounds and rock-hewn relieving arches.  Tripartite lancet arch window opening over entrance to east gable.  Lean-to porch to north-west, having double-leaf boarded door with strap hinges.  Nave with south aisle separated by pointed arcade on marble and limestone columns to interior, having timber west gallery.  Chancel reordered retaining altar and reredos.  Lady chapel to aisle with niche and carved altar.  Romanesque style font.  Exposed scissor trusses.  Gateway to site, built c. 1875, to north comprising pair of limestone ashlar Gothic Revival style piers with wrought-iron finials.  North boundary to site replaced with concrete block pier and chains.

NAME: Saint Bernard's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding six-bay single- and double-height International style Roman Catholic church, dated 1968, on an asymmetrical staggered plan possibly reusing fabric of earlier church on site to north elevation.  Comprising six-bay double-height nave with stepped copper-sheeted roof, spirelet to south and six-bay single-storey flat-roofed aisles to east and to west elevations.  Series of five pitched copper-sheeted roofs rising in height towards chancel, the highest section has a copper spire.  Concrete brick facing to walls with exposed concrete structure members and having carved limestone dedication plaque.  Timber framed vertical windows and entrance screens with granite thresholds.  Clerestory windows between roof sections appear to be formed from interlocking vertical panels of obscured glass.  Aisled interior with concrete columns around periphery.  Ceiling in timber boarded series of planes rising towards altar and with skylights between.  Polished black limestone font, altar, lectern and tabernacle pedestal.  Gothic Revival style organ.  Stone retaining wall to south west.

NAME: Saint Mary's Catholic Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding cruciform-plan five-bay double-height Roman Catholic church, dated 1849, originally single-cell barn style.  Comprising four-bay double-height nave with, two-bay single-storey sacristy to north elevation and having bellcote to west gable.  Renovated and extended, 1935, with single-bay double-height transepts added to north and to south elevations.  Renovated, 1979, with single-bay single-storey gabled projecting porch added to west gable end.  Pitched slate roofs with clay ridge tiles, gable parapets and having cast-iron gutters, decorative hoppers and downpipes.  Painted rendered walls with projecting eaves band.  Pointed arch openings with hood mouldings, trefoil heads to some openings with painted rusticated surrounds.  Leaded coloured glass panels.  Rose window above entrance.  Single and paired timber one-over-one pane sliding sash windows to sacristy, glazed with leaded panels of coloured glass.  Cruciform-plan interior with shallow chancel.  Open trussed roof with timber vault at crossing.  Plastered walls with beading at dado level.  Chancel reordered, retaining altar, reredos and lectern.  Distinctive altar carved with high-relief figures.  Concrete flagged steps and podium to front.

NAME: Kilflyn Church
COMPOSITION: Freestanding three-bay double-height former Church of Ireland church, built c. 1810, with single-bay two-stage truncated entrance tower to south-west gable end having bellcote over gable, and single-bay single-storey lean-to vestry projection to south.  Renovated with openings partly remodelled to accommodate use as heritage centre.  Pitched slate roof with bellcote to west gable and pedestal to east gable.
